'''Bryan Guy Adams''' {{Post-nominals|OC|OBC}} {{small|[[Royal Photographic Society|FRPS]]}} (born November 5, 1959) is a Canadian guitarist, singer, composer, and photographer. Adams has been cited as one of the [[List of best-selling music artists|best-selling music artists of all time]], and is estimated to have sold between 75 million<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/theater/ct-ae-pretty-woman-premiere-0311-story.html|title=An exclusive behind the scenes look at the 'Pretty Woman' musical, coming to Chicago|first=Chris|last=Jones|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=March 9, 2018|access-date=March 21, 2018}}</ref> and more than 100 million [[album|record]]s and [[Single (music)|single]]s worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/music/2013/09/10/brian_chater_helped_build_canadian_music_industry.html|title=Brian Chater helped build Canadian music industry|first=Nick|last=Krewen|date=September 10, 2013|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|access-date=December 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name="Star March 2022">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/music/2022/03/17/bryan-adams-on-family-bonding-writing-a-musical-and-releasing-upbeat-tunes-in-troubled-times.html|title=Bryan Adams On Family Bonding, Writing a Musical and Releasing Upbeat Tunes in Troubled Times|first=Nick|last=Krewen|date=March 17, 2022|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|access-date=April 16, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/A/Adams_Bryan/2004/12/01/753551.html|author=Armstrong, Denis|title=Bryan Adams not slowing down|date=December 1, 2004|publisher = [[Jam!]]|work = [[Ottawa Sun]]|access-date = August 15, 2010|url-status = dead|archive-url = https://archive.today/20120722163811/http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/A/Adams_Bryan/2004/12/01/753551.html|archive-date = July 22, 2012}}</ref> Adams was the most played artist on Canadian radio in the 2010s<ref>{{cite web|url=https://musiccanada.wordpress.com/2020/01/16/nielsen-music-canada-releases-decade-end-charts/|title=Nielsen Music Canada Releases Decade-End Charts|date=January 16, 2020|publisher=musiccanada.wordpress.com}}</ref> and has had 25 top-15 singles in Canada and a dozen or more in each of the US, UK, and Australia.

Adams joined his first band at age 15, and at age 20 his [[Bryan Adams (album)|eponymous debut album]] was released. He rose to fame in North America with the 1983 top ten album ''[[Cuts Like a Knife]]'', featuring its title track and the ballad "[[Straight from the Heart (Bryan Adams song)|Straight From the Heart]]", his first US top ten hit. His 1984 Canadian and US number one album, ''[[Reckless (Bryan Adams album)|Reckless]]'' (which became the first album by a Canadian to be certified diamond in Canada), made him a global star with tracks like "[[Run to You (Bryan Adams song)|Run to You]]" and "[[Summer of '69]]", both top ten hits in the US and Canada, and the power ballad "[[Heaven (Bryan Adams song)|Heaven]]", a US number one hit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mashable.com/2014/11/20/bryan-adams-reckless-turns-30/|title=Bryan Adams' iconic album 'Reckless' turns 30|first=Corinne|last=Bagish|date=November 20, 2014|publisher=Mashable.com}}</ref> His 1987 album ''[[Into the Fire (album)|Into the Fire]]'', with its US and Canadian top ten song, "[[Heat of the Night]]", rose to number two in Canada and the top ten in the US and several other countries.

In 1991, Adams released "[[(Everything I Do) I Do It for You]]", which went to number one in at least 19 countries, including for 16 and 18 straight weeks in the UK, and Europe overall, both records.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/(everything-i-do)-i-do-it-for-you/|title=Official Singles Chart, Bryan Adams (Everything I Do) I Do It for You|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|access-date=November 24, 2020}}</ref> It is one of the [[List of best-selling singles|best-selling singles]] of all time, having sold more than 15 million copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite news|title=Review/Pop; Bryan Adams, More Mr. Nice Guy|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/03/08/arts/review-pop-bryan-adams-more-mr-nice-guy.html|last=Pareles|first=Jon|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 8, 1994|access-date=November 24, 2020}}</ref> The song was included on Adams' ''[[Waking Up the Neighbours]]'' (1991), a worldwide number one album that sold 16 million copies, including being certified diamond in Canada.<ref name="WUTN">{{cite web|url=https://vanyaland.com/2016/09/18/remember-september-25-awesome-albums-turning-25-years-old-month/|title=Remember September: 25 awesome albums turning 25 years old this month|first=Michael|last= Marotta|date=September 18, 2016|work=vanyaland.com|access-date=December 5, 2020}}</ref> Another major hit off the album was the Canadian number one and US number two hit "[[Can't Stop This Thing We Started]]", which also went top ten in several other countries. Beginning in 1993, Adams' hits were mostly ballads, including the worldwide number one or two hits "[[Please Forgive Me]]" (1993); "[[All for Love (song)|All for Love]]" (1993); and "[[Have You Ever Really Loved a Woman?]]" (1995), the latter two topping the [[Billboard Hot 100|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Review/Pop; Bryan Adams, More Mr. Nice Guy|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/apr/11/bryan-adams-cancels-mississippi-tour-date-protest-of-anti-lgbt-law|last=Pareles|first=Jon|work=The New York Times|date=March 8, 1994|access-date=February 20, 2014}}</ref> Adam's 1993 greatest hits compilation album, ''[[So Far So Good (Bryan Adams album)|So Far So Good]]'', topped the charts in numerous countries selling 13 million copies worldwide, including being certified 6× platinum in the US and 11× platinum in Australia.

In 1996, Adams' ''[[18 til I Die]]'' was a top five album in many countries, but only reached number 31 in the US. He did duets with [[Barbra Streisand]] ("[[I Finally Found Someone]]" (1996), his last US top ten hit) and [[Melanie C]] ("[[When You're Gone (Bryan Adams song)|When You're Gone]]" (1998), an international top five hit). In the 1990s, Adams had six European Radio Airplay number one songs for 32 weeks, the fourth and third most, respectively; and three number one songs on the [[Eurochart Hot 100 Singles|European Sales Chart]] for 29 weeks total, the most weeks of any artist.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Music-and-Media/90s/1991/MM-1991-08-10.pdf|title=EHR Top 25|magazine=[[Music & Media]]|date=August 10, 1991|access-date=July 31, 2019}}</ref> Since 1999, Adams released eight albums, three reaching number one in Canada, and the last three reaching the top three in the UK, Germany and elsewhere in Europe.

In 2008, Adams was ranked 38th on the list of all-time top artists on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name="BillboardAllTime">[http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/specials/hot100/charts/top100-artists-40.shtml The Billboard Hot 100 All-Time Top Artists (40–21)] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20120525102509/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/specials/hot100/charts/top100-artists-40.shtml|date=May 25, 2012}} ''Billboard''. Retrieved August 1, 2015</ref> Adams has won 20 [[Juno Award]]s and a Grammy Award for [[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for Visual Media|Best Song Written for a Motion Picture or Television]] amongst 15 Grammy nominations, and has been nominated for five [[Golden Globe Award]]s and three [[Academy Award]]s for his songwriting for films.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/person/bryan-adams|title=Golden Globe Awards for 'Bryan Adams'|publisher=[[Golden Globe Awards]]|access-date=November 29, 2020}}</ref> Adams has been inducted into the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]], [[Canada's Walk of Fame]], the [[Canadian Broadcast Hall of Fame]],<ref name="Canada's Walk of Fame">{{cite web
|url=http://www.canadaswalkoffame.com/inductee/bryan-adams
|title=Canada's Walk of Fame
|access-date=September 1, 2008
|url-status=dead
|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080803213528/http://www.canadaswalkoffame.com/inductee/bryan-adams
|archive-date=August 3, 2008
}}</ref><ref name="CABHoF">{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcasting-history.ca/index3.html?url=http%3A//www.broadcasting-history.ca/personalities/personalities.php%3Fid%3D2|title=Member of CAB Hall of Fame|work=CAB Hall of Fame|access-date=September 1, 2008|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424012952/http://www.broadcasting-history.ca/index3.html?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.broadcasting-history.ca%2Fpersonalities%2Fpersonalities.php%3Fid%3D2|archive-date=April 24, 2016}}</ref> the [[Canadian Music Hall of Fame]]<ref name="Juno Awards">{{cite web|url= http://www.broadcastermagazine.com/news/1-7-million-viewers-for-the-2006-juno-awards-on-ctv/1000050442/?er=NA|title=1.7 Million Viewers For The 2006 JUNO Awards on CTV|work=broadcastermagazine.com|date= April 3, 2006|access-date=November 10, 2014}}</ref> and the Canadian Songwriters Hall of Fame.<ref name="Star March 2022"/> On May 1, 2010, Adams received the [[Governor General's Awards|Governor General's Performing Arts Award]] for his 30 years of contributions to the arts.<ref name="GGCA">{{cite web|url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=13614|title=Performing Arts Awards Ceremony|publisher=Gg.ca|access-date=September 22, 2014}}</ref>

== Life and career ==
=== Early life ===
Bryan Adams was born on November 5, 1959, in [[Kingston, Ontario|Kingston]], Ontario, Canada,<ref name="famechain">{{cite web|url=https://www.famechain.com/family-tree/15556/bryan-adams|title=Bryan Adams Family Tree & History, Ancestry & Genealogy – FameChain|website=FameChain|access-date=May 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://kingstonherald.com/entertainment/bryan-adams-award-2010314175|title= Bryan Adams to Receive Humanitarian Spirit Award at Canadian Music Week|first=Courtney|last=Hart|date= February 1, 2015|publisher=KingstonHerald.com <!--website, not a newspaper-->|access-date= April 11, 2016|quote=The Kingston-born artist's music career...|archive-date=September 12, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912021353/http://kingstonherald.com/entertainment/bryan-adams-award-2010314175|url-status=live}}</ref> to Elizabeth Jane (née Watson) and Captain Conrad J. Adams,<ref name="famechain" /> who emigrated to Canada from [[Plymouth]], England in the 1950s.<ref name=Telg3672213>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/3672213/The-charmed-life-of-Bryan-Adams.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220111/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/3672213/The-charmed-life-of-Bryan-Adams.html |archive-date=January 11, 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|title=The charmed life of Bryan Adams|first=David|last=Jenkins|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=March 30, 2008|access-date=May 5, 2012|location=London}}{{cbignore}}</ref> Adams' father, a [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst|Sandhurst]] officer in the [[British Army]], joined the [[Canadian Army]] and later worked as a United Nations peacekeeping observer and as a Canadian foreign service diplomat.<ref name=Telg3672213 /> Adams travelled with his parents to diplomatic postings in [[Lisbon]], Portugal (where he attended the [[Carlucci American International School of Lisbon|American International School of Lisbon]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cmjornal.pt/mais-cm/domingo/detalhe/a_escola_portuguesa_de_bryan_adams|title=A escola portuguesa de Bryan Adams|website=Cmjornal.pt}}</ref> and [[Vienna]], Austria (where he attended the [[American International School of Vienna]]), during the 1960s, and to [[Tel Aviv]], Israel during the early 1970s.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2002/jul/08/artsfeatures.features|title=Interview: Bryan Adams|last=Hattenstone|first=Simon|date=July 8, 2002|work=The Guardian|access-date=September 17, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Ruhlmann />

Raised in [[Ottawa]], Adams attended [[Colonel By Secondary School]] in the [[Beacon Hill, Ottawa|Beacon Hill]] neighbourhood of East Ottawa.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hercampus.com/school/u-ottawa/10-ottawa-born-or-raised-celebrities|title=10 Ottawa Born or Raised Celebrities|work=Her Campus|access-date=September 17, 2018}}</ref> In 1974, Adams, his mother, and younger brother Bruce moved to [[North Vancouver (district municipality)|North Vancouver]], while his father was posted abroad. While there, he attended [[Argyle Secondary School]] and Sutherland Secondary School.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/music/bryan-adams-drops-his-nostalgia-bombs-in-vancouver-show/article4320520/|title=Bryan Adams drops his nostalgia bombs in Vancouver show|website=The Globe and Mail|access-date=September 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/life/bryan-adamss-mom-rocks/article736209/|title=Bryan Adams's mom rocks!|work=The Globe and Mail|date=May 7, 2005|access-date=September 17, 2018}}</ref>

=== Early career ===
Adams bought his first [[electric guitar]] at the age of 12 in [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]], an Italian brand from Gherson, based on a [[Fender stratocaster]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B7yKSoTnA0z/?hl=it |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/iarchive/instagram/bryanadams/2229890026196176179 |archive-date=December 23, 2021 |url-access=subscription|title=Bryan Adams ì: "My first electric guitar was an italian Gherson guitar that looked like a Fender stratocaster|publisher=[[Instagram]]|access-date=December 28, 2020}}{{cbignore}}</ref> In an interview with music magazine ''[[Guitar World]]'', Adams said: <blockquote>"I bought an imitation Les Paul at a Five and Dime store in Ottawa, Canada, in 1971," Adams recalled. "Before that, I had an imitation Strat which I bought in Reading, England in 1970."

It felt real at the time to have a Les Paul, even though I'm a massive Ritchie Blackmore fan - still am. I was heavily into [[Humble Pie]]'s [[Performance Rockin' the Fillmore|''Rockin' the Fillmore'']] album at the time, and both [[Peter Frampton]] and [[Steve Marriott]] were on Les Pauls. It's rock guitar heaven, that album."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.guitarworld.com/news/bryan-adams-first-real-six-string|title=Bryan Adams reveals the identity of his "first real six-string"|author= Matt Owen|date=24 January 2022|publisher=[[Guitar World]]|access-date=16 February 2022}}</ref> </blockquote> He left school to play in a group called "Shock" and used the funds his parents had saved for his college education to buy an [[Estey Organ|Estey]] grand [[piano]] to tinker with.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.classicpopmag.com/2019/08/bryan-adams-interview-the-life-of-bryan/|title=Interview with Bryan Adams: 'I don't believe in the endings at all. I'd rather go on |first=John|last=Earls|website=classicpopmag.com|date=August 15, 2019 |access-date=December 29, 2020}}</ref> At one point he sold [[pet food]] and worked as a dishwasher in a restaurant, which paid the rent.<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.kansas.com/entertainment/music-news-reviews/article1099415.html|title=Bryan Adams: 'Sometimes songs they write themselves'|first=Bob|last=Curtright|date=September 20, 2012|publisher=kansas.com|access-date = December 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.radiocity.in/international/photo-gallery-details/10-things-you-didn%E2%80%99t-know-about-Bryan-Adams/1213|title=10 things you didn't know about Bryan Adams|first=Neha|last=Shetye|publisher=radiocity.in|access-date=December 29, 2020|archive-date=June 15, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210615090553/https://www.radiocity.in/international/photo-gallery-details/10-things-you-didn%E2%80%99t-know-about-Bryan-Adams/1213|url-status=dead}}</ref> He got into different bands such as [[Creedence Clearwater Revival|CCR]] and [[Deep Purple]], and attended concerts by [[Led Zeppelin]], [[T. Rex (band)|T. Rex]], [[Elton John]], and [[Tina Turner]]. He started working in the [[Vancouver]] music scene with bands and as a studio session singer. At the age of 15, he became the vocalist for a pub band, [[Sweeney Todd (band)|Sweeney Todd]].<ref name="Sweeney Todd">{{cite web|url=http://www.canadianbands.com/Sweeney%20Todd.html|title=Sweeney Todd – Canadian Bands.com|publisher=canadianbands.com|access-date=November 23, 2020}}</ref>
{{quote box|align=left|width=25em|quote="I met Bryan Adams by chance at Long & McQuade, a Vancouver music store, in January 1978. I was there with a friend musician Ali Monroe. She knew Bryan and she introduced us. We swapped phone numbers, got together a couple of days later, and over the next eleven years wrote dozens of songs for Bryan and a long list of recordings for other artists."|source= —[[Jim Vallance]], tells how they met with Adams and how their collaboration began.<ref name="Jim Vallance">{{cite web|url=http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/albums-folder/pg-album-adams-01-ba.html|title=Bryan Adams self-titled debut album|first=Jim|last=Vallance|author-link=Jim Vallance|publisher=jimvallance.com|access-date=23 November 2020|archive-date=16 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150816020004/http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/albums-folder/pg-album-adams-01-ba.html|url-status=dead}}</ref>}} Adams recorded "Roxy Roller" which came in at No. 99 on the US charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thjkoc.net/2010/11/05/roxy-roxy-roller-roller/|title=Roxy Roxy Roller Roller|date=November 5, 2010|author=JB|publisher=thjkoc.net|access-date=November 26, 2020}}</ref> This new incarnation of the band also released an album ''[[If Wishes Were Horses (album)|If Wishes Were Horses]]'' (1977) with Adams billed as "Bryan Guy Adams" on vocals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rateyourmusic.com/release/album/sweeney-todd/if-wishes-were-horses/|title=Sweeney Todd If Wishes Were Horses...|publisher=rateyourmusic.com|access-date=November 23, 2020}}</ref> Adams left the band at age 16.<ref name="Sweeney Todd" /> In 1978, at age 18, Adams met [[Jim Vallance]] through a mutual friend in a Vancouver Long and McQuade musical instrument store.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Friend |first=David |date=March 9, 2022 |title=Bryan Adams to be inducted into Canadian Songwriters Hall of Fame |work=CBC/The Canadian Press |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/bryan-adams-canadian-songwriters-hall-of-fame-1.6379842 |access-date=March 10, 2022}}</ref> Vallance was the former drummer and principal songwriter for Vancouver-based rock band [[Prism (band)|Prism]], and had recently quit that band to focus on a career as a studio musician and songwriter. They agreed to meet at Vallance's home studio a few days later. This proved to be the beginning of a partnership which was prolific and continuous through the 1980s, together they co-wrote for Adams and a long list of recordings for other artists, including [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]], [[Tina Turner]], [[Joe Cocker]], [[Johnny Hallyday]], [[Bonnie Raitt]], [[Rod Stewart]], [[Bonnie Tyler]], [[Loverboy]], [[Carly Simon]] and [[Neil Diamond]] to name a few,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/pg-discography.html|title= Jim Vallance Recorded Songs 1977–2019|first=Jim|last=Vallance|author-link=Jim Vallance|website=jimvallance.com|access-date=November 29, 2020}}</ref> and while discontinuous, {{as of|2017|lc=y}}, is still in existence.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.etonline.com/pretty-woman-musical-team-teases-sexy-and-true-broadway-adaptation-exclusive-91191|title='Pretty Woman: The Musical' Team Teases a Sexy and True Broadway Adaptation (Exclusive)|work=Entertainment Tonight|access-date=September 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/bryan-adams-pretty-woman-musical/|title=Bryan Adams Writes Score for 'Pretty Woman' Musical|website=Ultimate Classic Rock|access-date=September 17, 2018}}</ref>

Later in 1978, Adams signed to A&M records for one dollar.<ref>Saidman, page 47</ref> A&M remixed one of Adams' demos as a disco song "[[Let Me Take You Dancing]]", featuring Adams' vocals sped up to meet the 122 BPM dance tempo. The song made the Canadian ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' chart in March 1979 along with its B-side "Don't Turn Me Away".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/list.aspx?OCRText=let%20me%20take%20you%20dancing&Year=1979&p_ID=15|title=Results: RPM Weekly – Library and Archives Canada|publisher=Bac-lac.gc.ca|date= July 17, 2013|access-date=September 24, 2018}}</ref> In 1979, he made an agreement with Canadian manager [[Bruce Allen (manager)|Bruce Allen]], who at that time also worked for [[Bachman–Turner Overdrive]] and [[Loverboy]]; to this day Allen is still his manager.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6746076/bryan-adams-manager-bruce-allen-new-album-interview|title=Bryan Adams' Manager (of 30 Years) Bruce Allen on the Singer's New Album and Fellow Canadian The Weeknd's Rise|first=Karen|last=Bliss|date=October 30, 2015|access-date=January 12, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bruceallen.com/|title=Bruce Allen Talent official site|publisher=bruceallen.com}}</ref>

=== 1980s ===
Adams's [[Bryan Adams (album)|self-titled debut album]], mostly co-written with Jim Vallance, was released in February 1980. With the exception of "Remember" and "Wastin' Time", most of the album was recorded in October and November 1979 at Manta Studios and co-produced by Adams and Vallance.<ref name="Jim Vallance" /> The album was certified gold in Canada in 1986.<ref name=CRIA /> Singles released from it included "Give Me Your Love", "Remember" and "Hidin' from Love", with the latter having the most success, reaching number 64 on the Canadian [[RPM (magazine)|RPM]] Current Hit Radio chart; none reached the US Billboard Hot 100.

Adams's second album, ''[[You Want It You Got It]]'', was released in 1981 and contained the FM album-oriented rock radio hit, "Lonely Nights", which reached number three on the US Album Rock Tracks chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/albums-folder/pg-album-adams-02-you.html|title=Bryan Adams You Want It You Got It|publisher=jimvallance.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151102013945/http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/albums-folder/pg-album-adams-02-you.html|access-date=November 23, 2020|archive-date=November 2, 2015}}</ref> The same song was reinterpreted by [[Uriah Heep (band)|Uriah Heep]] for the album ''[[Head First (Uriah Heep album)|Head First]]'', released in 1983.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/songs-folder-may-27/pg-song-uriah-heep.html|title=Uriah Heep – Lonely Nights ("Between 1983 and 2006 Uriah Heep included" Lonely Nights "on at least sixteen albums ...")|publisher=jimvallance.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140813105356/http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/songs-folder-may-27/pg-song-uriah-heep.html|access-date=November 28, 2020|archive-date=August 13, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://metalodyssey.net/2010/07/05/uriah-heep-head-first-1983-hard-rockin-album-flashback/|title=Uriah Heep 1983 hard 'flashback rockin|date=July 6, 2010|publisher=Metal Odyssey|access-date=November 28, 2020}}</ref> The most successful song off the album in Canada was "Fits Ya Good" which reached the top 30 on the RPM Top 40 Chart; it also reached number 15 on the US Album Rock Tracks chart. From January to May 1982, Adams spent months traveling on his "You Want It You Got It Tour"; within a few months the album had been picked up across the United States and Adams was soon on tour doing clubs and noon hour concerts for radio stations, as well as support to such acts as [[The Kinks]] and [[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]].<ref name="Skole1">{{cite web|url=http://skolarbete.nu/skolarbeten/bryan-adams/|title=The Life Of Bryan|language=da|publisher=-skolarbete.nu|access-date=December 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130328170944/http://skolarbete.nu/skolarbeten/bryan-adams/|archive-date=March 28, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>

''[[Cuts Like a Knife]]'', which was released in January 1983, was Adams's breakout album.<ref name="jimvallance.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/albums-folder/pg-album-adams-03-cuts.html|title=Bryan Adams Cuts Like a Knife (album)|publisher=jimvallance.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306120429/http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/albums-folder/pg-album-adams-03-cuts.html|access-date=November 23, 2020|archive-date=March 6, 2014}}</ref> "[[Straight from the Heart (Bryan Adams song)|Straight from the Heart]]" was the first single released from the album; it reached number 10 on the [[Billboard Hot 100]],<ref name=US /><ref name="countrythangdaily.com">{{cite web|url=https://www.countrythangdaily.com/brian-adams-straight-heart/|title=Bryan Adams with his Hit, "Straight from the Heart"|date=October 31, 2018|publisher=countrythangdaily.com|access-date=November 26, 2020}}</ref> number 20 on the Canadian RPM Top 40 chart, and number one on the Canadian Adult Contemporary Chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.6294&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.6294.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.6294|title=Image : RPM Weekly|date=July 30, 1983|publisher=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|access-date=December 14, 2020}}</ref> In September 1983, [[Bonnie Tyler]] released her version for the studio album ''[[Faster Than the Speed of Night]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.countrythangdaily.com/bonnie-tyler-straight-heart/|title=Bonnie Tyler's "Straight From The Heart": Evokes Country Rock In 1980's|date=June 1, 2018|publisher=countrythangdaily.com|access-date=November 26, 2020}}</ref> The second single, "Cuts Like a Knife", rose to number 15 on the Billboard Hot 100, number six on the US Album Rock Tracks Chart,<ref name="web.archive.org">{{cite web|url=http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/songs-folder-may-27/pg-song-adams-cuts-like.html|title=Bryan Adams Cuts Like a Knife (single)|publisher=jimvallance.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403030227/http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/songs-folder-may-27/pg-song-adams-cuts-like.html|access-date=November 23, 2020|archive-date=April 3, 2015}}</ref> and number 12 on the Canadian RPM Top 40 Chart. The third single, "[[This Time (Bryan Adams song)|This Time]]", was also a top 30 hit in the US and Canada. Overseas, the latter two singles were both Top 20 hits in New Zealand, but there was little success in any other countries, aside from "Straight From the Heart" and "This Time" reaching the top 50 in the UK. Three other tracks, "Take Me Back", "I'm Ready" and "The Only One", also received substantial airplay on North American rock radio stations, each making the US Album Rock Tracks chart. The album peaked at number eight on both the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] album chart<ref name="Bryan Adams">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/bryan-adams-p3502/charts-awards|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110403065707/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/bryan-adams-p3502/charts-awards|url-status=dead|archive-date=April 3, 2011|title=Bryan Adams|website=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=September 15, 2019}}</ref> and in Canada, achieving three times platinum status in Canada, platinum status in the United States and gold status in Australia.<ref name="CRIA" /><ref name=US /><ref name="ARIA" /> In August, Adams began recording his third album at Vancouver's [[Little Mountain Sound Studios]].<ref name="Skole1" />

In October, Adams joined [[Jim Vallance]] at the Yamaha Music Festival in Japan. In December 1982, Captain Annan, Bryan Adams, and [[Loverboy]] played at [[The Forum (Inglewood, California)|Los Angeles Forum]] in California.<ref name="Skole1" /> [[Music Express (magazine)|Music Express]] the national popular opinion poll voted him Canada's best male singer for 1982. In March 1983, Adams travelled to America, opening for [[Journey (band)|Journey]] and performing on over 100 dates in five months.<ref name="Skole1" /> Adams featured on "[[American Bandstand]]".<ref name="Skole1" /> In April 1983, a breather in the program is used to shoot a video for the third single "This Time" at [[Edwards Air Force Base]] in California. The video is directed by Steve Barron with photography by [[László Kovács (cinematographer)|László Kovács]].<ref name="Skole1" /> In May 1983, he briefly interrupted the tour with Journey to direct the club [[The Bottom Line (venue)|The Bottom Line]] in [[New York City]].<ref name="Skole1" /> In the audience were [[Mick Jagger]], [[Nils Lofgren]], Rick Nielson (Cheap Trick), [[Gene Simmons]], [[Paul Stanley]] and [[John McEnroe]].<ref name="Skole1" /> [[Paul Dean (guitarist)|Paul Dean]] of Loverboy, [[John Waite]] and [[Rick Derringer]] joined him on stage.<ref name="Skole1" /> On July 30, 1983, he performed at [[Day on the Green]], sharing the stage with [[Journey (band)|Journey]], [[Triumph (band)|Triumph]], [[Eddie Money]] and [[Night Ranger]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://davidkaufer.com/2011/01/29/music-memories-day-on-the-green-in-1983/|title=Music Memories: Day on the Green in 1983|publisher=Davidkaufer.com|access-date= December 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://landtradio.com/day-on-the-green-1983-1/|title=Day on the Green #1|date=July 30, 2019|publisher=landtradio.com|access-date= December 3, 2020}}</ref>

In August 1983, Adams's tour with Journey concluded, and in September 1983 Adams performed with [[Supertramp]] in front of a crowd of over 30,000 Vancouver fans at [[BC Place]].<ref name="Skole1" /> In the following months he performed in eleven countries on a six-week solo tour of Europe. While in Germany, he records the popular rock TV show "[[Rockpalast]]".<ref name="Skole1" /> In November 1983, Adams is on tour in Japan and by the end of the year he had performed 283 concerts. A&M released the film soundtrack of the album "[[A Night in Heaven]]", with the power ballad "[[Heaven (Bryan Adams song)|Heaven]]",<ref name="Skole1" /> on it. "Heaven" reached number nine on the US [[Album-oriented rock|AOR]] Rock Tracks chart and became the title of a "SOR" tour of Western Canada.<ref name="Skole1" /> In December 1983, his numerous music industry awards for the year include Best Selling New Artist (The National Association of Record Merchandisers), number two Male [[Album-oriented rock|AOR]] Artist (The Album Network) and number three most played album AOR (Radio & Records), as well as the [[Juno Awards]] for the best male singer.<ref name="Skole1" /> In January 1984, Adams and Vallance began writing for the next album, while in February 1984 Adams toured Australia, New Zealand, and [[Hawaii]] with [[The Police]].<ref name="Skole1" />

The album ''[[Reckless (Bryan Adams album)|Reckless]]'' was released in late 1984, and peaked at number one on both the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and the Canadian Album Chart, while reaching number two in Australia and number seven in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/albums-folder/pg-album-adams-04-reck.html|title=Bryan Adams Reckless|publisher=jimvallance.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306120434/http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/albums-folder/pg-album-adams-04-reck.html|access-date=November 23, 2020|archive-date=March 6, 2014}}</ref> The album featured six singles: "[[Run to You (Bryan Adams song)|Run to You]]", "[[Somebody (Bryan Adams song)|Somebody]]", "[[Heaven (Bryan Adams song)|Heaven]]", "[[Summer of '69]]", "[[One Night Love Affair]]", and "[[It's Only Love (Bryan Adams song)|It's Only Love]]", a duet with the female star and "[[Honorific nicknames in popular music|Queen of Rock 'n' Roll]]" [[Tina Turner]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-world-of-tina.com/its-only-love---single.html|title=It's Only Love (1985)|website=the-world-of-tina.com|access-date=December 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name="It's Only Love">{{cite web|url=http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/songs-folder-may-27/pg-song-adams-its-only-lov.html|title=Bryan Adams with Tina Turner It's Only Love|publisher=jimvallance.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140304195741/http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/songs-folder-may-27/pg-song-adams-its-only-lov.html|access-date=November 23, 2020|archive-date=March 4, 2014}}</ref> All six singles peaked in the Top 15 of the US Billboard Hot 100, only the third album to achieve this<ref name="It's Only Love" /> with the rockers "Run to You" (number six) and "Summer of '69" (number five) peaking in the top ten, and the ballad "Heaven" reaching number one. "Run To You" was the most successful single at album-oriented rock stations in the US, as it spent four weeks at the top of the mainstream rock tracks chart; "Somebody" reached number one for a single week on that chart; while "It's Only Love" and "One Light Love Affair" each rose to number 7. "Summer of '69" had gotten a minor amount of airplay upon the initial release of the album, making it ineligible to re-chart on the mainstream rock track chart when it was released as single in summer 1985.
