|title="Heaven" (1985)
|description  = Recorded in 1983, written by Adams and [[Jim Vallance]], it was later included on the album ''[[Reckless (Bryan Adams album)|Reckless]]'' by Adams in 1984. It was released as ''Reckless's'' third single and reached number one on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in June 1985.
|format       = [[Ogg]]
}}
"Run To You" was the biggest hit off ''Reckless'' in Canada reaching number four, with "Summer of '69" and "Heaven" both peaking at number 11, "Somebody" peaking at number 13, "It's Only Love" hitting number 14, and "One Night Love Affair" reaching number 19. "Summer of 69" also reached the top ten in New Zealand and Norway, and the Top 20 in Sweden, Australia and Austria, but only peaked at number 42 in the UK and number 62 in West Germany. Adams has stated that "Summer of '69" was not a success when initially released in the UK because British radio stations did not add it to their play lists like they had "Run To You".<ref name="BBC News">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-47473120|title=Bryan Adams explains why Summer of 69 flopped in the UK|first=Mark|last=Savage|date=March 7, 2019|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=December 15, 2020}}</ref> However, it gained popularity over time and was certified Platinum (600,000) in sales in the UK in 2019, and its Spotify streams were at 280 million as of 2019, twice that of "(Everything I Do) I Do For You."<ref name="BBC News" /> In the Low Countries it achieved its maximum popularity in 1990 when it peaked at number 4 in 17 weeks on the Netherlands' singles chart,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dutchcharts.nl/search.asp?search=summer%20of%20%2769&cat=s|title=Dutch Charts,Zoeken naar: summer of '69|date=July 21, 1990|publisher=[[Dutch Charts]]|access-date=December 14, 2020|
language=nl}}</ref> and reached number 8 on the Belgium chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultratop.be/nl/song/1be1/Bryan-Adams-Summer-Of-'69|title=Ultratop.be, Bryan Adams Summer of '69|publisher=[[Ultratop]]|access-date=December 14, 2020|
language=nl}}</ref>

"It's Only Love" was nominated for a [[Grammy Award]] for Best Rock Vocal Performance by a Duo or Group in 1986. In 1986, the song won an MTV award for [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Stage Performance|Best Stage Performance]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=zGAVAAAAIBAJ&pg=5978,1934262&dq|title=British band, its leader top Grammy nominees|date=January 10, 1986|work=[[The Register-Guard]]|publisher=Guard Publishing|access-date=December 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/tina-turners-lifetime-grammy-gold-2532222628.html|title=Jewels for the Queen: Tina Turner's Lifetime of Grammy Gold|date=February 9, 2018|website=[[PopMatters]]|access-date=November 28, 2020}}</ref> ''Reckless'' also earned Adams a Grammy nomination for Best Male Rock Performance.<ref name=Ruhlmann>{{cite web|last=Ruhlmann|first=William|title=Bryan Adams: Classical Entry|publisher=allmusic|url=http://www.arkivmusic.com/classical/Name/Bryan-Adams/Composer/46-1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125190855/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/bryan-adams-q71156|archive-date=November 25, 2010|url-status=live|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref> In December 1984, Adams embarked on a two-year world tour to launch the album starting in Canada and United States, then into Japan, Australia, back to the UK, where for dates he supported Tina Turner for her [[Private Dancer Tour]], and again to Canada. After winning four Juno Awards, he headed south towards the American West Coast, culminating with two dates at the Paladium in Los Angeles.<ref name="Skole">{{cite web
|url=http://skolarbete.nu/skolarbeten/bryan-adams/
|title=The Life of Bryan
|language=da
|publisher=skolarbete.nu
|access-date=June 24, 2008
|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130328170944/http://skolarbete.nu/skolarbeten/bryan-adams/
|archive-date=March 28, 2013
|url-status=dead
}}</ref>{{failed verification|date=September 2019}} ''Reckless'' eventually went Diamond in sales in Canada, the first album by a Canadian artist to do so, while reaching 5× and 3× Platinum in the US and UK. ''Reckless'' has sold over 12 million copies worldwide, and won the [[Juno Award for Album of the Year]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/stories/bryan-adams-reckless-album/|title=FEATURES'Reckless': Revisiting Bryan Adams' Stadium-Sized Classic|first=Ryan|last= Healy|date=November 5, 2020|work=[[Universal Music Group]]|access-date=December 5, 2020}}</ref>

1985 was an intense and demanding year. On February 10, he recorded the Northern Lights single "[[Tears Are Not Enough]]", an improvised supergroup with [[Joni Mitchell]], [[Neil Young]] and other Canadian artists. Adams was the author of the lyrics and the album, the mission was to raise funds to help the [[1983-85 famine in Ethiopia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jonimitchell.com/library/print.cfm?id=1858|title=The Northern Lights sparkle for fans and famine victims|first= Liam|last=Lacey|date=February 11, 1985|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|publisher=jonimitchell.com|access-date=December 2, 2020}}</ref> The song was issued as a single by [[Columbia Records]] in March of that year,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mcintosh|first1=Andrew|title=Tears Are Not Enough|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/tears-are-not-enough-emc|website=The Canadian Encyclopedia|access-date=December 2, 2020|language=en|date=February 22, 2016}}</ref> and quickly reached number one on the Canadian [[Top 40]] chart. It also finished number one on the year-end Canadian charts for 1985. The song's video also received extensive airplay on [[MuchMusic]]. Participation was incredible: the single went triple platinum immediately,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://musiccanada.com/gold-platinum/?_gp_search=Northern%20Lights&_gp_certification=triple-platinum-physical-singles|title=Gold/Platinum, Certification Northern Lights Tears Are Not Enough|date=May 1, 1985|publisher=[[Music Canada]]|access-date=December 2, 2020}}</ref> although independently recorded by the USA for Africa project, it was included in the full-length ''[[We Are the World (album)|We Are the World]]'' album. On July 13, Adams attended the [[Live Aid]] concert, from [[Philadelphia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pennlive.com/life/2020/07/live-aid-1985-was-literally-a-life-saving-concert-for-one-man-35-years-ago.html|title=Live Aid 1985 was literally a life-saving concert for one man 35 years ago|first=Deb|last=Kiner|date=July 13, 2020|publisher=[[The Patriot-News]]|access-date=December 2, 2020}}</ref> He took the stage at [[John F. Kennedy Stadium (Philadelphia)|JFK Stadium]] in front of over 100,000 people and the band played "Kids Wanna Rock", "Summer Of '69" and "Cuts Like A Knife", before concluding with "Tears Are Not Enough".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://liveaid.free.fr/rewind/bbc/pages/038bryanadams.html|title=Live Aid (July 13th, 1985): Bryan Adams|publisher=liveaid.free.fr|access-date=December 2, 2020}}</ref> Bryan Adams sang a small passage of this song on [[Live 8 concert, Barrie|Live 8]] in [[Barrie]] during [[All for Love (song)|All For Love]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Barrie wins Canadian Live 8 concert|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/barrie-wins-canadian-live-8-concert-1.534372|access-date=December 2, 2020|publisher=[[CBC News]]|date=June 21, 2005}}</ref>

In September 1985, Adams worked on [[Roger Daltrey]]'s sixth solo album ''[[Under a Raging Moon (album)|Under a Raging Moon]]''. The album was a tribute to [[The Who]]'s drummer [[Keith Moon]], who died in 1978.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/albums-folder/pg-album-daltrey-1.html|title=Roger Daltrey Under a Raging Moon|publisher=jimvallance.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106064427/http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/albums-folder/pg-album-daltrey-1.html|access-date=November 23, 2020|archive-date=November 6, 2014}}</ref> Adams co-wrote two tracks for the album: "[[Let Me Down Easy (Roger Daltrey song)|Let Me Down Easy]]" and "Rebel".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/songs-folder-may-27/pg-song-daltrey-let-me.html|title=Roger Daltrey Let Me Down Easy|publisher=jimvallance.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106050956/http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/songs-folder-may-27/pg-song-daltrey-let-me.html|access-date=November 23, 2020|archive-date=November 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/songs-folder-may-27/pg-song-daltrey-rebel.html|title=Roger Daltrey Rebel|publisher=jimvallance.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106064429/http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/songs-folder-may-27/pg-song-daltrey-rebel.html|access-date=November 23, 2020|archive-date=November 6, 2014}}</ref> The track "Let Me Down Easy" was a Top 15 Hit on [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'s [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Mainstream Rock Tracks]]. Nearly 30 years later, Adams would release his own version of "Let Me Down Easy" on a 30-year anniversary version of ''Reckless''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bryanadams.com/index.php?target=discography,albums&view_releases=list&show_release=488|publisher=Bryan Adams Official Website|title=Bryan Adams discography|access-date=February 20, 2015}}</ref>

In January 1986, Adams provided the ending background vocals to the song "[[Don't Forget Me (When I'm Gone)]]" by Canadian rock band [[Glass Tiger]] for their debut album ''[[The Thin Red Line (album)|The Thin Red Line]]''. It reached number one in Canada and number two in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/songs-folder-may-27/pg-song-glass-tgr-don%27t-fo.html|title=Glass Tiger Don't Forget Me (When I'm Gone)|publisher=jimvallance.com|access-date=November 23, 2020}}</ref>

His follow-up album to ''Reckless'' was ''[[Into the Fire (album)|Into the Fire]]'' (1987). This album contained the hit songs "[[Heat of the Night]]", which went to the top ten in both Canada and the US, and "[[Hearts on Fire (Bryan Adams song)|Hearts on Fire]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/albums-folder/pg-album-adams-05-into.html|title=Bryan Adams Into the Fire (album)|publisher=jimvallance.com|access-date=November 23, 2020|archive-date=May 7, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140507031658/http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/albums-folder/pg-album-adams-05-into.html|url-status=dead}}</ref> In December 1987, Adams contributed the song "[[Run Rudolph Run]]" to the album ''[[A Very Special Christmas (album)|A Very Special Christmas]]'', which benefited the Special Olympics.<ref>{{cite book|last=McGee|first=Matt|title=U2: A Diary|publisher =[[Omnibus Press]]|year=2008|pages=111|isbn = 978-1-84772-108-2}}</ref> The album was certified [[RIAA certification|quadruple platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] for shipment of four million copies in the United States,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?content_selector=gold-platinum-searchable-database#|title=RIAA Searchable Database|work=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|access-date=November 30, 2020|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140830055854/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?content_selector=gold-platinum-searchable-database|archive-date=August 30, 2014}}</ref> is the 19th [[List of best-selling Christmas albums in the United States|best-selling Christmas/holiday album in the United States]] during the SoundScan era are 2,520,000 copies sold.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/6334706/holidays-biggest-radio-and-album-hits|title=The Gifts That Keep on Giving: Biggest Radio and Album Hits of the Holidays|author=<!--Not stated-->|magazine=Billboard|date=December 1, 2014|access-date=November 30, 2020}}</ref> In May 1988, [[Tommy Mandel]] joined the Adams band as new [[keyboardist]]. A last-minute hometown gig was scheduled for 86 Street Music Hall on 24 and tickets sell out within 7 minutes of going on sale. [[Jon Bon Jovi]] and [[David Bryan]] joined in on stage, together playing "[[Born to Be Wild]]". Adams donated the entire proceeds to [[leukemia]] research at a presentation at [[British Columbia Children's Hospital]].<ref name="Skole1" /> In June 1989, teams up with famed producer/composer [[Robert John "Mutt" Lange]] at London's [[Olympic Studios]] to write more material for the upcoming LP. Bryan attended a press conference on June 8 to launch the North American release of Rainbow Warriors, and also joined artists to re-record the classic [[Deep Purple]] hit "[[Smoke On The Water]]" in aid of [[1988 Armenian earthquake|Armenian earthquake]] victims.<ref name="Skole1" /> In July 1989, Adams returned to Vancouver's [[Little Mountain Sound Studios]] to record more songs for the lp with [[Bob Clearmountain]]. Adams and [[Keith Scott (musician)|Keith Scott]] attended the [[David Foster]] celebrity softball tournament banquet in Victoria, B.C. – an annual fundraiser for [[kidney]] research.<ref name="Skole1" /> In August 1989, he recorded the backup vocals for the [[Belinda Carlisle]] song "Whatever It Takes" from the ''[[Runaway Horses (album)|Runaway Horses]]'' album. Also during that time, Adams contributed to [[Mötley Crüe]]'s work on the album ''[[Dr. Feelgood (album)|Dr. Feelgood]]'', doing the backing vocals of "Sticky Sweet" and [[Charlie Sexton]] doing the backing vocals of "Don't Look Back" from the ''[[Charlie Sexton (album)|Charlie Sexton]]'' album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rockandmetalinmyblood.com/recensioni/motley-crue-dr-feelgood/1989-elektra-records/485/|title=Mötley Crüe Dr. Feelgood|first=Tatiana|last=Madlena|date=January 8, 2015|website=rockandmetalinmyblood.com|access-date=December 10, 2020|language=it}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/feature/dr-feelgood-motley-crues-track-by-track-guide-to-1989-classic-90524/|title="Dr. Feelgood": Motley Crue's Track By Track Guide to 1989 Classic|first=Andy|last=Greene|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=May 5, 2005|access-date=December 10, 2020}}</ref> In October 1989, Adams performed two club benefit concerts at 86 Street Music Hall in Vancouver on 18 & 19. "A Night for the Environment" raised $40,000.00 for four local environmental groups. Bryan is nominated for a Gemini Award for Best Performance (Music) for CBS's "Live In Belgium" television special.<ref name="Skole1" /> In November 1989, Adams flew to London, England on the 18th for press interviews for the upcoming shows of [[New Year's Eve#Japan|New Year's Eve]] in Japan. He resumes writing material for the album with Mutt Lange and attends Tina Turner's 50th birthday party at London's prestigious [[Reform Club]].

In December 1989, the long-awaited first live LP was released. Entitled ''[[Live! Live! Live!]]'', it was recorded live at the [[Rock Werchter]] festival on July 3, 1988, in [[Werchter]], Belgium. Adams returned to Little Mountain Sound Studios mid-month to record even more material for the next album. The release date was tentatively scheduled for April 1990.

=== 1990s ===
[[File:Bryanadams en argentina.jpg|thumb|left|Adams in 1990]]
Adams, along with [[Don Henley]], [[Huey Lewis]], [[Michael Monroe]] and [[Loudness (band)|Loudness]] kicked off the 90s with two New Year's Eve shows on December 31 and January 1 at the 70,000-seat Japanese [[Tokyo Dome]].<ref name="Skole1" /> He promptly headed back to the London studios for continuous album production and optimistically anticipated a very busy new decade. In February 1990, Adams and his guitarist and Keith Scott flew to [[Los Angeles]] on February 21 to take part in Grammy Week Live – a collection of 15 radio stations broadcast live from the Roosevelt Hotel. On the 23rd, Bryan performed a special show on stage at [[A&M Records|A&M]] Charlie Chapman for radio Pollack Media Convention executives.<ref name="Skole1" />

In the spring of 1990, Adams presented "Album of the Year" to [[Alannah Myles]] at the Canadian Juno Awards in [[Toronto]] on the 18th.<ref name="Skole1" /> He returned to London and joined [[Eric Carmen]] in the studio to record the backing vocals for "Feels Like Forever", a song written by Adams for Eric's then-upcoming LP.<ref name="Skole1" /> Production of the Adams project continued with Mutt Lange in England for the next two months. In June 1990, he received the prestigious "Order Of British Columbia Award" at a ceremony in [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]] on the 21st.<ref name="Skole1" /> He starred in two European festivals in [[Midtfyns Festival|Midfyns]] and [[Roskilde Festival|Rosskilde]], Denmark, on June 28.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loudmemories.com/concert/bryan-adams-at-roskilde-festival-1990-festival-461175|title=Bryan Adams Roskilde Festival 1990 – Roskilde, Denmark|date=June 28, 1990|publisher=loudmemories.com|access-date=December 3, 2020}}</ref> Other top performers included fellow Canadian [[Jeff Healey]], [[Little Feat]] and [[Bob Dylan]].<ref name="Skole1" /> Adams added vocal tracks on the melody of [[David Foster]] "River Of Love" in his home studio in [[Vancouver]]. On 21 July 1990, Adams took part in [[Roger Waters]]'s concert production of ''The Wall - Live In Berlin'', to commemorate the fall of the Berlin Wall eight months earlier. Adams performed the Pink Floyd track "Young Lust." A live album and video of the concert was released in August 1990.

On August 17, 1990, Adams headlined "Live At The Park", an outdoor festival in [[Calgary]], Alberta. Also on the bill were [[The Pursuit of Happiness (band)|The Pursuit of Happiness]] and [[Paul Laine]] from Vancouver. Over 27,000 fans attended the festival.<ref name="Skole1" /> Tour photographer [[Andrew Catlin]] was in town for photo sessions with Bryan and the band for the next album and Much Music interviews him for a special Artist of the Decade. On the international front, the 1985 LP "Reckless" and the single "Summer of '69" climbed the charts in the Netherlands to number 10 and number 4 respectively.<ref name="Skole1" />

In September 1990, Adams sang the national anthem to officially kick off the first race [[Molson Indy Vancouver]] of Vancouver held on September 2.<ref name="Skole1" /> He received Humanitarian Award of the Year from Local Maple Ridge Hospital Foundation, but was unable to attend the 29th awards gala as Adams and the band were on their way to South America for a three-day freedom celebration.<ref name="Skole1" /> They performed on September 28 in [[Chile]] in the huge 55,000-seat [[Estadio Nacional Julio Martínez Prádanos]] in [[Santiago]], then headed to [[Buenos Aires]], in Argentina, the next day to perform alongside [[David Bowie]] and [[Mick Taylor]] at [[Estadio Monumental Antonio Vespucio Liberti]].<ref name=Kinder>{{cite web|last=Kinder|first=Paul|title=The Sound+Vision Tour|url=http://www.bowiewonderworld.com/tours/tour90.htm|access-date=December 3, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425174935/http://www.bowiewonderworld.com/tours/tour90.htm|archive-date=April 25, 2012}}</ref> The local press hailed his performance as a classic punchy rock & roll show. It has conquered a relatively unknown market.<ref name="Skole1" /> In December 1990, recording continued in England for most of the month. Adams returned home for vacation with family and friends. ''Live! Live! Live!'' was certified gold in Japan, commemorating the sale of over 50,000 units.<ref name="Skole1" />

At the beginning of 1991, Adams returned to London on the sixth to start mixing with Mutt Lange. The release date for ''Waking Up The Neighbors'' was scheduled for the end of April. European festival dates were announced with [[ZZ Top]] in June.<ref name="Skole1" /> In the months of February and March 1991, the recording and mixing continued in London. [[The Law (English band)|The Law]] recorded 'Nature Of The Beast' – a melody written by Adams and Vallance. Adams joins them in the studio to lend vocals and guitar tracks.<ref name="Skole1" /> In April 1991, Adams and Mutt Lange wrote and recorded "[[(Everything I Do) I Do It For You]]" for the ''[[Robin Hood: Prince Of Thieves]]'' soundtrack.<ref name="Skole1" /> In May 1991, directed by [[Julien Temple]], the video for the song was shot in [[Sheffield]], England on May 17 and 18. Rehearsals for the next European tour began with ZZ Top. In June 1991, a video was shot for the first single album "[[Can't Stop This Thing We Started]]" 'directed by [[Kevin Godley]] at [[Pinewood Studios]] in London. On the eighth, Adams kicked off the headlining tour at the "Jubeck Festival" in Germany.<ref name="Skole1" /> On the 17th, he performed a private show for a personal service recently returned from the [[Gulf War]] at the Canadian Armed Forces base in [[Baden Baden]], Germany. 

On September 24, 1991, the album ''[[Waking Up the Neighbours]]'' was released. Co-produced by Adams and [[Robert John "Mutt" Lange]], it topped the charts around the world, including in the UK, Canada, Australia and Germany and reached number six on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.1665&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.1665.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.1665 | title=RPM 100 Albums |magazine=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|date=November 2, 1991|access-date=November 22, 2021}}</ref><ref name="US">{{cite web
|url={{AllMusic|class=artist|id=p3502|pure_url=yes}}
|title=Artist Chart History – Bryan Adams
|publisher=Allmusic
|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110217214823/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/p3502
|archive-date=February 17, 2011
|access-date=November 12, 2013}}</ref> It became Adams's second album to be certified Diamond in sales in Canada while being certified 5× platinum in the US. It went on to sell 16 million copies worldwide.<ref name="WUTN" /> ''Waking up the Neighbors'' became the first album by a Canadian since Neil Young's 1972 ''[[Harvest (Neil Young album)|Harvest]]'' to reach the top of the album charts in the United Kingdom. Ironically, however, the album was launched in Canada amidst a storm of controversy. The album is also known to have caused controversy in Canada due to the [[Canadian content]] system.<ref name="Canadian Content">{{cite web|url=http://archives.cbc.ca/economy_business/the_media/topics/1150-6306/|title=Bryan Adams not Canadian?|publisher=Ruling the Airwaves: The CRTC and Canadian Content|access-date=December 5, 2020}}</ref> This indicated that a certain percentage must be broadcast by Canadian music on Canadian radio and television broadcasts. Since ''Waking Up the Neighbors'' was largely recorded in England and co-produced by [[Robert John "Mutt" Lange]] (originally from [[Zambia]]), the album and its songs, under the rules in effect until 1991, were not considered purely Canadian productions.<ref name="Canadian Content" /> The album managed to reach the top of the Canadian charts.<ref name="Canadian Content" /> Following Adams' complaints, in September of that year, the [[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]] (CRTC) announced that the [[Canadian content]] rules would be expanded. The regulation at that time considered collaborative writing between Canadians and non-Canadians to be "Canadian" only where the lyricist and musical composer worked separately and at least one was Canadian.  In protest, Adams briefly threatened to boycott Canada's annual [[Juno Awards]], where his album was eventually almost completely ignored by the awards committee. He did end up winning the [[Juno International Achievement Award]], [[Canadian Entertainer of the Year]] (voted on by the public) and [[Jack Richardson Producer of the Year Award|Producer of the Year Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pabsttheater.org/bryanadams|title=Bryan Adams biography|publisher=pabsttheater.org|access-date=December 5, 2020|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120716111958/http://pabsttheater.org/bryanadams|archive-date=July 16, 2012}}</ref>  In September 1991, the regulation was amended to recognize collaborations in which two (or more) contributors each contributed to both lyrics and music, as was the case with Adams and Lange. 
