It was followed in 1995 by "[[Have You Ever Really Loved a Woman?]]". It was a number one in the US, Canada and Australia, as well as a top five hit in the UK and Germany.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/#/artist/bryan-adams/chart-history/3925?f=305&g=Albums|title=Bryan Adams > Album & Song Chart History > Billboard 200|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=November 28, 2020}}</ref> The single was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Song|Oscar]], [[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for Visual Media|Grammy]] and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/song/have-you-ever-really-loved-woman|title=Golden Globe Awards for Golden Globe Awards for 'Have You Ever Really Loved a Woman?'|publisher=[[Golden Globe Award]]|access-date=November 29, 2020|archive-date=October 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201031013832/https://www.goldenglobes.com/song/have-you-ever-really-loved-woman|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3g4EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA56|title=Best-Selling Records of 1995|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=January 20, 1996|access-date=November 23, 2020|page=56|issn=0006-2510|volume=108|number=3}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.9218&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.9218.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.9218|title=Top RPM Adult Contemporary: Issue 9218|journal=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|date=July 17, 2013|access-date=November 23, 2020}}</ref>

In June 1996, the album ''[[18 til I Die]]'' was released. It contained three singles (including two UK top ten singles): "[[The Only Thing That Looks Good on Me Is You]]",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.3034&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.3034.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.3034|title=Top RPM Singles: Issue 3034.|publisher=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|work=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|date=July 17, 2013|access-date=November 29, 2020}}</ref> "[[Let's Make a Night to Remember]]" (both reached number one in Canada),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.9911&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.9911.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.9911|title=Top RPM Singles: Issue 9911.|publisher=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|work=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|date=July 17, 2013|access-date=November 29, 2020}}</ref> and "[[Have You Ever Really Loved a Woman?]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.9224&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.9224.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.9224|title=Top RPM Singles: Issue 9224.|publisher=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|work=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|access-date=November 29, 2020}}</ref> The album features the single "[[Star (Bryan Adams song)|Star]]". The song is included in the soundtrack of the film ''[[Jack (1996 film)|Jack]]''; directed by [[Francis Ford Coppola]], with [[Robin Williams]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0116669/soundtrack|title=Jack (1996) Soundtracks|publisher=[[IMDb]]|access-date=November 29, 2020}}</ref> The film co-stars [[Diane Lane]], [[Jennifer Lopez]], [[Fran Drescher]], [[Bill Cosby]] and [[Brian Kerwin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0116669/?ref_=ttsnd_snd_tt|title=Jack (1996)|publisher=[[IMDb]]|access-date=November 29, 2020}}</ref> The album reached the top spot on the UK charts for Adams's third UK number one studio album in a row<ref>{{cite web |title=Bryan Adams |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/17982/bryan-adams/ |website=Official Charts |access-date=13 August 2022}}</ref> while also reaching the top ten in several other countries, such as number two in Australia and number four in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Bryan+Adams&titel=18+%27Til+I+Die&cat=a|title=Australian Charts – Bryan Adams – 18 til I Die|publisher=australiancharts.com.|access-date=November 29, 2020}}</ref> The album was less successful in the US only reaching number 31 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], but was certified platinum in the United States by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]].<ref name="RIAA">{{cite web
|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=Lostprophets&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=&before=&startMonth=1&endMonth=1&startYear=1958&endYear=2007&sort=Artist&perPage=25
