In November 1996, "[[I Finally Found Someone]]" was released is a song recorded by Bryan Adams and the American singer [[Barbra Streisand]]. The song was part of the soundtrack of Streisand's self-directed film ''[[The Mirror Has Two Faces]]'' and was nominated for an [[Academy Awards]] and [[Golden Globe Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/song/ive-finally-found-someone|title=Golden Globe Awards for 'I've Finally Found Someone'|publisher=[[Golden Globe Award]]|access-date=November 29, 2020|archive-date=August 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200812123424/https://www.goldenglobes.com/song/ive-finally-found-someone|url-status=dead}}</ref>

In November 1997, he participated in writing the song ''[[Let's Talk About Love]]'' by [[Celine Dion]], which became one of the [[List of best-selling albums|best-selling albums in history]].<ref>''Let's Talk About Love'' worldwide sales:
* {{cite news|first=Jason|last=Anderson|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/books/learning-to-love-cline-dion/article16178/|title=Learning to Love Celine Dion|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|date=January 19, 2008|access-date=December 9, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090921140631/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/books/learning-to-love-cline-dion/article16178/|archive-date=September 21, 2009|url-status=live}}
* {{cite web|title=The 50 best-selling albums ever|work=[[NME]]|url=https://www.nme.com/photos/the-50-best-selling-albums-ever/195120/1/1#32|date=October 21, 2010|access-date=December 9, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140816201949/http://www.nme.com/photos/the-50-best-selling-albums-ever/195120/1/1#32|archive-date=August 16, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The song is by the French singer-songwriter and record producer of 1987's [[Jean-Jacques Goldman]] "[[Puisque tu pars]]", the song was recorded with English lyrics by Adams and [[Eliot Kennedy]] as "Let's Talk About Love".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celinedionweb.com/en/music/let-s-talk-about-love/|title=Let's talk about love|website=CelineDionWeb.com|access-date=December 9, 2020}}</ref> In 1999, a demo version of Adams' translation appeared on the single CD "[[Cloud Number Nine]]" in 1999. In December 1997, Adams released ''[[Unplugged (Bryan Adams album)|MTV Unplugged]]'' with three new tracks: "[[Back to You (Bryan Adams song)|Back to You]]", "A Little Love" and "When You Love Someone". "[[Back to You (Bryan Adams song)|Back to You]]" was the first single, followed by "[[I'm Ready (Bryan Adams song)|I'm Ready]]", an acoustic version of the song from the album ''Cuts Like A Knife''. The album was a top ten success in Germany while both singles reached the top 20 in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-chart/19971214/7501/|title=Official Singles Chart top ten0 (14 December 1997 – 20 December 1997)|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|access-date=November 23, 2020}}</ref>

''[[On a Day Like Today (album)|On a Day Like Today]]'' was released in 1998 and the release coincided with his contract being sold to [[Interscope Records]]. ''On a Day Like Today'' enjoyed success internationally, entering the top five in Germany and Canada and was certified platinum in the UK. It generated two British top ten singles: "Cloud Number Nine" and "When You're Gone", which featured [[Melanie C]] of the [[Spice Girls]] and peaked at number 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-chart/19981206/7501/|title=Official Singles Chart top ten0(06 December 1998 – 12 December 1998)|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|access-date=November 23, 2020}}</ref> The song has sold 830,000 combined equivalent-sales in the UK as of May 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/10-girl-group-stars-who-went-it-alone__8768/|title=10 girl group stars who went it alone|last=Myers|first=Justin|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|date=May 31, 2019|access-date=November 23, 2020}}</ref>

To commemorate the millennium, Adams released ''[[The Best of Me (Bryan Adams album)|The Best of Me]]'', his most comprehensive collection of songs at that time, which included two new songs, the title track "The Best of Me" and the UK number one track "[[Don't Give Up (Chicane song)|Don't Give Up]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/8911/chicane-ft-bryan-adams/|title=Chicane feat Bryan Adams|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|date=March 18, 2000|access-date=November 29, 2020}}</ref> The album reached the top ten in Germany and was certified three times platinum in Canada and Platinum in the UK. The single from the album, "The Best of Me" was a successful hit with the exception of the US, where neither the single or the album were released by [[Interscope Records]], the single peaked at 10 on the [[Canadian Singles Chart]] on January 24, 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.9695&volume=70&issue=12&issue_dt=January%2024%202000&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=1eslr84up6jai4j6cngk0p4cu2|title=The Best of Me – Canadian Singles Chart|publisher=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|access-date=November 29, 2020}}</ref> On November 26, 1999, he participated as a guest in the celebration of Tina Turner's 60th birthday. It was recorded in [[London]] and after 14 years, Turner once again performed with Adams the songs "It's Only Love" and the new song "Without You" on Tina's album ''[[Twenty Four Seven (Tina Turner album)|Twenty Four Seven]]'', Adams guests on both the title track and "Without You". A DVD Celebrate! Of the evening was released November 21, 2000 ''Celebrate! - 60th Birthday Special''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-world-of-tina.com/celebrate---video.html|title=Celebrate! (1999)|date= November 26, 1999|website=the-world-of-tina.com|access-date=December 11, 2020}}</ref> On the night between December 31, 1999, and January 1, 2000, at [[Bell Center]] in Montreal in front of 20,000 people, Adams participated in [[Celine Dion]]'s "Millennium Concert", to celebrate the arrival of the new millennium. In the evening, at the entrance to the stage he sang "[[Summer of '69]]", then he duetted with Celine Dion on the songs "[[It's Only Love (Bryan Adams song)|It's Only Love]]", "[[When You're Gone (Bryan Adams song)|When You're Gone]]" and concluded with" [[(Everything I Do) I Do It for You]] ".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celinedionweb.com/en/event/la-derniere-concert/|title=La dernière de Céline Concert (Québec)|website=CelineDionWeb.com|access-date=December 9, 2020}}</ref>

=== 2000s ===
In October 2000, Adams participated at [[Madison Square Garden]] in the concert of [[Elton John]] from which the CD and DVD ''[[Elton John One Night Only – The Greatest Hits]]'' was released. The album, the result of performances over two evenings (in spite of the title "One Night Only"), contains the most popular songs by Elton John performed live, chosen from those performed during the two concerts (therefore it does not contain the full track-list). Many of these are actually duets between the rock star and other famous names in the world music scene: Adams duets with Elton John on the track [[Sad Songs (Say So Much)|Sad Songs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eltonjohnitaly.com/onenightonly.html|title= Elton John – One Night Only (2000)|work=eltonjohnitaly.com|language=it|access-date=December 4, 2020}}</ref> On August 26, 2000, he performed at the [[Slane Festival]] in front of over 70,000 people, with special appearances by [[Melanie C]], [[Chicane (musician)|Chicane]] and [[Davy Spillane]]. The concert was also released on CD/DVD.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bryanadams.com/album/live-at-slane-castle-ireland/|title= Bryan Adams live at Slane Castle (Ireland 2000)|publisher=bryanadams.com|access-date=December 4, 2020}}</ref> On November 27 of the same year, Adams took part in the benefit concert [[The Who & Special Guests: Live at the Royal Albert Hall|Live at the Royal Albert Hall]] organized by [[The Who]] (but also open to several other artists), singing a song by the English band, [[Behind Blue Eyes]] and [[See Me, Feel Me]] with [[Eddie Vedder]]. The concert was also released on CD as ''[[Live at the Royal Albert Hall (The Who album)|Live at the Royal Albert Hall]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewho.com/music/live-at-the-royal-albert-hall/|title=The Who Live at Royal Albert Hall|publisher=[[The Who]]|access-date=December 4, 2020}}</ref> Adams co-wrote and performed the songs for the DreamWorks animated film ''[[Spirit: Stallion of the Cimarron]]'' in 2002. The songs were included on the [[Spirit: Stallion of the Cimarron (soundtrack)|film's soundtrack]]. The most successful single from the soundtrack was "[[Here I Am (Bryan Adams song)|Here I Am]]", a British top five and German Top 20 hit. The song also gave him his fourth [[Golden Globe Award]] nomination for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song#2000s|Best Song from a Motion Picture]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/song/here-i-am|title=Golden Globe Awards for '"Here I Am"'|publisher=[[Golden Globe Award]]|access-date=November 29, 2020|archive-date=April 26, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426023621/http://www.goldenglobes.com/song/here-i-am|url-status=dead}}</ref>

In 2004, ARC Weekly released its chart of top pop artists since the last 25 years and Adams came up at number 13 in the chart with four number-one singles, ten top five hits and 17 Top-10 hits. Six years after the release of ''On a Day Like Today'', ''[[Room Service (Bryan Adams album)|Room Service]]'' was released in September 2004. It topped the charts in Germany and Switzerland and peaked at number four in the UK, selling 440,000 copies in its first week in Europe and thus debuted at number one on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'''s European album chart. The single, "[[Open Road (Bryan Adams song)|Open Road]]", was the most successful single from the album and peaked at number one in Canada and number twenty-one in the UK. In May 2008, the album was also released in the US but charted only at number 134 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.canada.com/theprovince/news/etoday/story.html?id=3737818e-2690-4a47-ab2a-25632813a7a7&k=3148|title=Bryan Adams and Wal-Mart team for album|publisher=[[Reuters]] Canada|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=April 10, 2004|access-date=November 29, 2020|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109015848/http://www.canada.com/theprovince/news/etoday/story.html?id=3737818e-2690-4a47-ab2a-25632813a7a7&k=3148|archive-date=November 9, 2012}}</ref> While touring in North America to promote the album, Adams shared the stage for about 25 concert tours with [[Def Leppard]], giving a completely new meaning to the phrase "take me out to the ball game" as co-headliner of the Rock 'N Roll Double-Header Tour. He joined for the first time and performed at 26 minor league [[baseball park]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20050307006024/en/Def-Leppard-and-Bryan-Adams-Bring-Major-League-Rock-N-Roll-to-Americas-Minor-League-Baseball-Parks-This-Summer-on-Cross-Country-Rock-N-Roll-Double-Header-Tour|title=Def Leppard and Bryan Adams Bring Major League Rock 'N Roll to America's Minor League Baseball Parks This Summer on Cross-Country ''Rock 'N Roll Double-Header'' Tour|date=March 7, 2005|location=[[Los Angeles]]|work=[[Business Wire]]|access-date=December 4, 2020}}</ref>
{{quote box|align=left|width=25em|quote="Tonight's inductee into the Hall of Fame is fantastic and I love him very much and he just hugged me backstage, which was, to be honest, arousing. He has played in over 72 countries [wow] and played for over 8 people. Oh 88 million people with sales of so many albums, you couldn't fit them in Canada. He is a Grammy, Juno, American Music Award, People Magazine, Oscar winner, Golden Globe Nominee, an officer of Canadian Customs [oh no!] The Order of Canada. He's pretty amazing, that's the point of this Wait, wait, wait...
Any great thing, like Live8 or Live Aid, he's always there. He's a crucial part of it and that's kind of all I've got to say about him. He's fantastic. He's a National Treasure for you and for the whole world, really and whenever there's a Canadian flag waving, he's proud to say he's part of that community. He's Bryan Adams and that's all there is to know about him... The newest addition to the Canadian Music Hall of Fame is Bryan Adams."|source=—[[Chris Martin]], introducing Adams to the [[Canadian Music Hall of Fame]], April 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coldplaying.com/chris-martin-bryan-adams-is-a-canadian-national-treasure/|title=Chris Martin: Bryan Adams Is A Canadian National Treasure|date=5 April 2006|publisher=coldplaying.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150519002414/http://www.coldplaying.com/chris-martin-bryan-adams-is-a-canadian-national-treasure/|access-date=29 November 2020|archive-date=19 May 2015}}</ref>}}

In 2006, Adams co-wrote and performed the theme song "Never Let Go" which was featured in the closing credits of the film ''[[The Guardian (2006 film)|The Guardian]]''. In April 2006, he was inducted into the [[Canadian Music Hall of Fame]]. Also in 2006, Adams co-wrote the [[Grammy Award]]-winning gospel song "[[Never Gonna Break My Faith]]"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/50th-annual-grammy-awards-2007|title=50th Annual GRAMMY Awards|date=November 28, 2017|website=GRAMMY.com}}</ref> for Aretha Franklin. It was featured in the film ''[[Bobby (2006 film)|Bobby]]'' as a duet by [[Aretha Franklin]] and [[Mary J. Blige]] with the [[Boys Choir of Harlem]] and earned him a [[Golden Globe]] Nomination in 2007.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/news/id/42
|title=64th Golden Globe Awards Nominations
|work=Golden Globe
|date=December 14, 2006
|access-date= September 1, 2008|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080327053001/http://www.goldenglobes.org/news/id/42 <!-- Bot retrieved archive -->|archive-date = March 27, 2008}}</ref> On July 31 of the same year, together with [[Billy Joel]], he performed in a free concert with an estimated crowd of over 500,000 people in [[Rome]] at [[Via dei Fori Imperiali]], with the [[Colosseum]] as a background.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/entertainment/joel-and-adams-in-free-rome-concert-270269.html|title=Joel and Adams in free Rome concert|date=August 1, 2006|work=irishexaminer.com|access-date=December 12, 2020}}</ref> Adams opened the concert with "So Far So Good", then after about an hour it was Joel's turn to take the stage. At the end the two artists gave the audience three encores, performing "[[You May Be Right]]", "[[Cuts Like a Knife (song)|Cuts Like a Knife]]" and "[[Piano Man (song)|Piano Man]]" together for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|language=it|url=https://www.repubblica.it/2006/07/sezioni/spettacoli_e_cultura/concerto-colosseo/telecomcerto-roma/telecomcerto-roma.html|title=Notte di musica al Colosseo in 500 mila per Adams e Joel|date=July 31, 2006|location=[[Rome]]|newspaper=[[la Repubblica]]|access-date=December 12, 2020}}</ref>

In May 2007, on the occasion of his 25th concert at the [[Wembley Arena]], he received the "Wembley Square Of Fame" at the plaque in the Square of Fame. A bronze plaque engraved with the name and handprints was unveiled. The place to celebrate the most famous and beloved artists who have made their mark on stage here over the years is located at [[Wembley Park]] in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wembleypark.com/attractions/square-of-fame/|title=The Square of Fame|website=wembleypark.com|access-date=December 6, 2020}}</ref>{{clarify|date=August 2022}} Adams has performed on several occasions at Wembley Park, 4 times at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]] in 1988 ([[Nelson Mandela 70th Birthday Tribute]]), 1992 ([[Waking Up the Neighbours|Waking Up the World Tour]]), 1996 ([[18 til I Die]] Tour), and 1999 ([[NetAid]]). At [[Wembley Arena]] he has performed 28 times, first on March 14, 1985, in support of [[Tina Turner]]. To date, 32 dates have taken place between "Wembley Stadium" and" Wembley Arena".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hillingdontimes.co.uk/news/1391603.bryan-adams-prints-the-square/|first=Alex|last= Ali|date=May 11, 2007|title=Bryan Adams prints the square|website=hillingdontimes.co.uk|access-date=December 6, 2020}}</ref>

In 2007, he co-wrote two songs "A Place for Us" and "Another Layer" for the Disney film ''[[Bridge to Terabithia (2007 film)|Bridge to Terabithia]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bridge to Terabithia Soundtracks|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0398808/soundtrack|website=IMDb.com|publisher=IMDb|access-date=September 16, 2019}}</ref>

Adams released his eleventh album, ''[[11 (Bryan Adams album)|11]]'', internationally on March 17, 2008. The album was released in the US at [[Wal-Mart]] and [[Sam's Club]] retail stores on May 13, 2008.<ref name="Wal-Mart secures album exclusive">{{cite web
|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1045920/wal-mart-secures-bryan-adams-album-exclusive
|title=Wal-Mart secures album exclusive
|work=Billboard.com
|date=April 8, 2008
|access-date=June 24, 2008}}</ref> The first single released from the album was "[[I Thought I'd Seen Everything (Bryan Adams song)|I Thought I'd Seen Everything]]". Adams did an 11-day, 11-country European acoustic promotional tour to kick off the release of the album.<ref name="usatoday">{{cite news
|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/2008-03-20-coming-attractions_N.htm
|title=Coming attractions: Bryan Adams is down to the '11' hour
|newspaper=USA Today
|access-date=June 24, 2008
|first1=Anthony
|last1=Breznican
|first2=Edna
|last2=Gundersen
|first3=Bill
|last3=Keveney
|date=March 20, 2008}}</ref> The album debuted at number one in Canada (making it his first album to reach that position since ''[[Waking Up the Neighbours]]'' in 1991) as well as reaching number two in Germany. In the United States, the album charted at number 80.<ref name=US /> Following the release of the album, the full-band tour started during the summer; on some dates in the United States he shared the stage with the rock band [[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]] and on others with his friend [[Rod Stewart]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.antimusic.com/news/08/june/25Bryan_Adams_Plans_Tours_With_Foreigner_and_Rod_Stewart.shtml|title=Bryan Adams Plans Tours With Foreigner and Rod Stewart|date=June 25, 2008|work=antimusic.com|access-date= December 4, 2020}}</ref>

Adams was one of four musicians who were pictured on the second series of the Canadian Recording Artist Series to be issued by [[Canada Post stamp releases (2005–2009)|Canada Post stamps]] on July 2, 2009,<ref>Canada Post Stamp Details, July to September 2009, Volume XVIII, No. 3, p. 6</ref> with estimated one and one-half million Adams stamps printed.<ref name="Bryan Adams gets the stamp of approval">{{cite web
|url          = http://www.stampnews.com/stamps/stamps_2009/stamp_1231781459_695809.html
|title        = Bryan Adams gets the stamp of approval
|author       = Vancouver Sun
|publisher    = StampNews.com
|date         = January 12, 2009
|access-date  = February 7, 2011
|archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110603072112/http://www.stampnews.com/stamps/stamps_2009/stamp_1231781459_695809.html
|archive-date = June 3, 2011
|url-status     = dead
|df           = dmy-all
}}</ref>
[[File:Bryan Adams 20120726 002-2.jpg|thumb|Adams and [[Keith Scott (musician)|Keith Scott]] during concert at the [[Poznań International Fair]], Poznań]]
On June 26, 2009, he performed on an episode of ''[[CMT Crossroads]]'' with [[Jason Aldean]], among the song repertoire of the two singers: "[[Heaven (Bryan Adams song)|Heaven]]", "[[Summer of '69]]", "[[Johnny Cash (Tracy Byrd song)|Johnny Cash]]", "[[She's Country]]", "[[Hicktown]]", "[[Run to You (Bryan Adams song)|Run to You]]" to name a few.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://clevelandcountrymagazine.com/jason-aldean-and-bryan-adams-on-cmt-crossroads/|title=Jason Aldean and Bryan Adams on CMT Crossroads|first=Charlie|last=Kriak|date=January 3, 2019|work=clevelandcountrymagazine.com|access-date=November 26, 2020}}</ref> One of the many highlights from the concert was "Heaven". Aldean poured his heart out singing lead on the song and Adams supported on harmonies during the chorus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.countrythangdaily.com/heavenbryanadams-j-aldean/|title="Heaven" with the Legend Bryan Adams featuring Jason Aldean|date=October 17, 2018|publisher=countrythangdaily.com|access-date=November 26, 2020}}</ref>

In December 2009, he co-wrote, produced, and performed the song "[[You've Been a Friend to Me]]" for the film ''[[Old Dogs (film)|Old Dogs]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2009/WORLD/europe/12/01/bryan.adams.interview/|title=The melody maker – CNN.com|website=edition.cnn.com|language=en|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref>

=== 2010s ===
In February 2010, Adams released "[[One World, One Flame]]". On February 12, 2010, Adams performed a duet with [[Nelly Furtado]]. The song was called "[[Bang the Drum (Bryan Adams song)|Bang the Drum]]" and was co-written with Jim Vallance for the [[2010 Winter Olympics opening ceremony|opening ceremony for the 2010 Winter Olympic Games]] in Vancouver, [[British Columbia]]. The ceremony was held indoors at [[BC Place Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sugarslam.com/bryan-adams-duet-with-nelly-furtado-at-olympics-opening-ceremony/|title=Bryan Adams Duet With Nelly Furtado At Olympics Opening Ceremony|last=Mess|first=Hot|publisher=sugarslam.com|date=February 13, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150407083419/http://www.sugarslam.com/bryan-adams-duet-with-nelly-furtado-at-olympics-opening-ceremony/|access-date=November 23, 2020|archive-date=April 7, 2015}}</ref>

Adams was one of several Canadian musicians to visit Canadian Prime Minister [[Stephen Harper]] at his official residence. Originally, the visit was meant to be Adams's plea to the Prime Minister to change copyright laws;<ref name="MacLeans Magazine">{{cite web|url=http://www.macleans.ca/2012/04/03/straight-from-the-heart/|title=Bryan Adams still sings straight from the heart|work=MacLeans Magazine|date=April 3, 2012|access-date=October 19, 2012}}</ref> instead, Harper turned it into an informal "[[jam session]]".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/article/811276--bryan-adams-jams-with-stephen-harper?bn=1|title=Bryan Adams jams with Stephen Harper|work=Toronto Star|date=May 19, 2010|access-date=July 9, 2010}}</ref>

In November 2010, Adams released the acoustic album ''[[Bare Bones (Bryan Adams album)|Bare Bones]]''. It is a live project consisting of twenty songs, to celebrate thirty years of career. The album is the result of two and a half years of acoustic concerts all sold out, offered mainly in many US city theaters in 2010. The booklet shows the recordings made on the dates of Concord, Providence, Binghamton, Orono and Williamsport. To accompany the singer-songwriter on the piano, appears the member of his band [[Gary Breit]]. Following the acoustic album, a long tour entitled "The Bare Bones Tour" is organized; has continuity with the previous 11 Tour/Acoustic Show took place in territories around the world, which began in February 2010 and ended in October 2014 for a total of 326 dates. It was certified gold in India a year later.<ref name="deccanchronicle.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/tabloids/straight-heart-570|title=Straight from the heart|work=Deccan Chronicle|date=February 14, 2011|access-date=November 1, 2011|archive-date=November 23, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123051757/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/tabloids/straight-heart-570|url-status=dead}}</ref>

On February 19, 2011, Adams and his band played in [[Kathmandu]], which was organized by ODC Network and made him the first international artist to perform in Nepal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehimalayantimes.com/fullNews.php?headline=Bryan+Adams+cuts+history+like+a+knife+in+Nepal&NewsID=277006|title=Bryan Adams cuts history like a knife in Nepal|work=The Himalayan Times|access-date=November 1, 2011|archive-date=April 9, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140409225022/http://www.thehimalayantimes.com/fullNews.php?headline=Bryan+Adams+cuts+history+like+a+knife+in+Nepal&NewsID=277006|url-status=dead}}</ref> He performed at the opening ceremony of the [[2011 Cricket World Cup]] on February 17, 2011, in [[Dhaka]], Bangladesh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/newDesign/news-details.php?nid=173378|title=Bryan Adams to Perform at ICC World Cup Opening in Dhaka|last=Bhattacharya|first=Pallab|date=February 9, 2011|work=Daily Star|access-date=February 26, 2011}}</ref> and also performed in a solo concert in the next day.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/newDesign/news-details.php?nid=174837|title=Bryan Adams Romances Dhaka|last=Sadique|first=Kazim Ibn|date=February 21, 2011|work=Daily Star.net|access-date=February 26, 2011}}</ref> In August 2013, ''[[Live at Sydney Opera House]]'' was released; it was recorded during one of the 3 nights at [[Sydney Opera House]], in August 2011, during "The Bare Bones Tour".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocktopia.co.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4572:bryan-adams-the-bare-bones-tour-live-at-sydney-opera-house&catid=911:dvd-a-blu-ray-reviews&Itemid=123|title=DVD & Blu-ray Reviews Bryan Adams – 'The Bare Bones Tour: Live At Sydney Opera House|first=Dave|last= Scott|date=January 8, 2014|work=rocktopia.co.uk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924091830/http://www.rocktopia.co.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4572:bryan-adams-the-bare-bones-tour-live-at-sydney-opera-house&catid=911:dvd-a-blu-ray-reviews&Itemid=123|access-date=December 4, 2020|archive-date=September 24, 2015}}</ref> It is available as a CD / DVD set or separately as a CD, DVD or [[Blu-ray]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bryanadams.com/album/live-at-sydney-opera-house-dvd-cd/|title=Live At Sidney Opera House|publisher=bryanadams.com|access-date=December 4, 2020|archive-date=January 18, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210118012351/https://www.bryanadams.com/album/live-at-sydney-opera-house-dvd-cd/|url-status=dead}}</ref> In April 2013, To Be Loved, the new album by [[Michael Bublé]], is released. The tracklist includes "After All", one of four original tracks, written by Bryan Adams, [[Alan Chang]], Steven Sater and [[Jim Vallance]], which sees the crooner duet with Adams, his countryman as well as an idol since childhood.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.panorama.it/news/musica/michael-buble-to-be-loved-recensione|title=Michael Bublé: la recensione di To be loved|first=Tony|last=Romano|date=April 17, 2013|work=[[Panorama (magazine)|Panorama]]|language=it|access-date=December 7, 2020}}</ref>

In an interview on March 18, 2014, Adams revealed that he has signed a contract with [[Verve Records]] in the US. With one album celebrating the 30th Anniversary of ''[[Reckless (Bryan Adams album)|Reckless]]'', a new album of covers. On September 30, 2014, Adams released a new album titled ''[[Tracks of My Years]]''. The album reached number one on the Canadian album chart. The album contains cover songs and one original song co-written with Jim Vallance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockcellarmagazine.com/2014/08/25/bryan-adams-new-album-tracks-of-my-years/#sthash.4LqIYXQZ.jmloRBPS.dpbs|title=Bryan Adams Announces 'Tracks of My Years', Due Out 9/30|work=Rock Cellar Magazine|date=August 26, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826114526/http://www.rockcellarmagazine.com/2014/08/25/bryan-adams-new-album-tracks-of-my-years/#sthash.4LqIYXQZ.jmloRBPS.dpbs|access-date=November 23, 2020|archive-date=August 26, 2014}}</ref> In July 2014, Adams filmed ''Bryan Adams in Concert'' for the American program ''[[Great Performances]]'' on [[PBS]]. It was recorded at the [[Elgin and Winter Garden Theatres|Elgin Theatre]] in Toronto and first shown on American Public Television on March 2, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/gperf/bryan-adams-concert-preview/3803/|title=Bryan Adams in Concert ~ Preview – Great Performances – PBS|work=Great Performances|date=February 13, 2015}}</ref>

Adams released his first album of all new material in seven years on October 16, 2015. The album, titled ''[[Get Up (Bryan Adams album)|Get Up]]'', was co-written with Jim Vallance and produced by [[Jeff Lynne]]. On September 7, 2015, it was announced that Adams would be performing at the [[2015 AFL Grand Final]], along with English singer [[Ellie Goulding]] and American musician [[Chris Isaak]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Twomey|first1=Callum|title=Adams, Goulding, Isaak headline GF show|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/2015-09-07/bryan-adams-chris-isaak-headline-grand-final-entertainment|website=afl.com.au|publisher=Australian Football League|access-date=September 7, 2015}}</ref> On December 31, 2015, he performed at the [[Methodist Central Hall, Westminster|Central Hall Westminster]] in [[London]] for the [[BBC's New Year's Eve]], which was broadcast live on [[BBC One]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2015/bryan-adams-bbc-nye|title=BBC- Bryan Adams to perform at exclusive BBC New Year's Eve concert|publisher=BBC|access-date=December 7, 2020}}</ref> The concert was divided into two parts, interrupted at the stroke of midnight by traditional fireworks was seen and was seen by about 12 million spectators in Great Britain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.barb.co.uk/viewing-data/weekly-top-30/|title=Weekly top 30 programmes on TV sets (July 1998 – Sept 2018)|publisher=barb.co.uk|access-date=December 7, 2020}}Select: on the '''"Channel"''' box: BBC1 (SD + HD),on the '''"Year"''' box select 2016, on the '''"Month"''' box select January, in the '''"Week"''' section select the date Dec 28 – Jan. 3</ref> On October 14, 2016, as announced by Adams himself in his channels during the summer, the Wembley 1996 DVD was released. This is the recording of his concert, as part of the 18 Til I die tour, held on July 27, 1996, at London's [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]], in front of over 70,000 spectators<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bryanadams.com/news/wembley-1996-live-available-october-14th/|title=Wembley 1996|publisher=bryanadams.com|access-date=December 7, 2020|archive-date=November 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201129140532/https://www.bryanadams.com/news/wembley-1996-live-available-october-14th/|url-status=dead}}</ref> The DVD immediately leaps to the top of the British industry charts.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/music-video-chart/20161016/13/|title=Official Music Video Chart top 50 (16 October 2016 – 22 October 2016)|date=October 16, 2016|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|access-date=December 7, 2020}}</ref>

On September 21, 2017, Adams announced via social media his release of a new compilation album, ''[[Ultimate (Bryan Adams album)|Ultimate]]'', with two new songs "Please Stay" and the anti-war themed "Ultimate Love", on November 3, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BZUMr-Vg8YA/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/iarchive/s/instagram/BZUMr-Vg8YA |archive-date=December 23, 2021 |url-access=subscription|title=Ultimate|publisher=Bryan Adams on Instagram|date=September 21, 2017|access-date=September 22, 2017}}{{cbignore}}</ref> Bryan Adams performed "the Ultimate tour" during the year 2018. He toured Australia, New Zealand, UK, Europe, the US, and Canada. He also brought the ultimate tour 2018 to India in the month of October 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://warmstrings.com/6-facts-you-didnt-know-about-bryan-adams/|title=6 facts you didn't know about Bryan Adams|date=December 30, 2018|language=en-US|access-date=August 29, 2019}}</ref> where he performed at Ahmedabad, Mumbai, Hyderabad, [https://warmstrings.com/6-facts-you-didnt-know-about-bryan-adams/ Bangalore], and Delhi.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bryanadams.com/tour/india-2018/|title=The Ultimate Tour India 2018|last=Official|first=Bryan Adams|date=August 15, 2018|website=Bryan Adams Official|language=en-US|access-date=August 29, 2019|archive-date=December 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191203125717/https://www.bryanadams.com/tour/india-2018/|url-status=dead}}</ref>

[[File:Bryan Adams Rimini 9.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|Adams with longtime guitarist Keith Scott,on the Get Up Tour 2017]]
Adams and his music are popular in India, where he is a household name for three generations of people,<ref name="Why India Will Always Run to Bryan Adams">{{cite web|url=https://www.arre.co.in/music/cloud-number-9-what-explains-bryan-adams-enduring-popularity-in-india/|title=Why India Will Always Run to Bryan Adams|publisher=arre.co.in|access-date=November 23, 2020}}</ref> and many people say the first few English phrases mastered by many young Indians are "It was the summer of '69" and "Everything I do, I do it for you."<ref name="Bryan Adams' star burns brightly in India">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/world/2011/02/11/bryan_adams_star_burns_brightly_in_india.html|title=Bryan Adams' star burns brightly in India|last=Westhead|first=Rick|work=thestar.com|date=February 11, 2011|access-date=November 23, 2020}}</ref> Many music industry executives have said Adams is the most-known foreign music artist in India, with a Universal Music India executive saying in 2011, "The only other performer who comes close is [[Enrique Iglesias]]. Bryan is huge.<ref name="Bryan Adams' star burns brightly in India" /><ref>{{cite news|url= https://qz.com/india/1422034/why-bryan-adams-songs-are-still-so-popular-in-india/|title=Indians love Bryan Adams because 'Summer of 69' is almost a Hindi song now|last=Ghosh|first=Devarsi|newspaper=Quartz|publisher=qz.com|date=October 12, 2018|access-date=23 November 2020}}</ref> He was one of the first foreigners to stage a large-scale concert in India in the early 1990s, and he has returned to tour India several times.<ref name="Bryan Adams' star burns brightly in India" /> Adams was on the cover of the September 2018 issue of ''Rolling Stone India'', within which they printed an interview with him; the article stated that Adams is "one rock legend whose concerts have created mass frenzy every single time in every single city he's played" in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.magzter.com/article/Music/RollingStone-India/Cant-Stop-This-Thing-We-Started-Bryan-Adams-Is-Back-In-India|title=Can't Stop This Thing We Started Bryan Adams Is Back In India!|last=Singh|first=Nirmika|publisher=RollingStone India|date=September 2018|access-date=23 November 2020}}</ref> It is also reported that "Summer of '69" has been so popular in India for so long that it is "almost a Hindi song now", often the only "western" song that might be allowed to be played at a traditional Indian wedding.<ref name="Bryan Adams' star burns brightly in India" /> One Indian writer wrote "From wedding parties to school farewells, in every gathering of people intoxicated beyond a certain level comes a time when someone slips on 'Summer of '69'. I'll bet you my Aadhaar number that as that song builds, there'll come a point where everyone in the room is triumphantly pumping their fists in the air and screaming, 'Those were the BEST DAYS of my life!'"<ref name="Why India Will Always Run to Bryan Adams" />

In August 2018, Adams performed a duet version of "Summer of '69" with [[Taylor Swift]] during her [[Taylor Swift's Reputation Stadium Tour|Reputation Tour]] in Toronto, Canada.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8468681/taylor-swift-bryan-adams-summer-of-69-live-toronto|title=Taylor Swift Surprises Toronto Crowd With Bryan Adams 'Summer of '69' Duet: Watch|date=August 5, 2018|access-date=December 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430222102/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8468681/taylor-swift-bryan-adams-summer-of-69-live-toronto|archive-date=April 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.countrythangdaily.com/taylor-swift-bryan-adams/|title=Taylor Swift: An Iconic Duet with Bryan Adams,"Summer of 69"|date=November 5, 2020|publisher=countrythangdaily.com|access-date=December 7, 2020}}</ref> Adams released his fourteenth album ''[[Shine A Light (Bryan Adams album)|Shine A Light]]'' on March 1, 2019. The album features collaborations with [[Ed Sheeran]] and [[Jennifer Lopez]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/bryan-adams-album-1.4982296|title=Bryan Adams enlists Ed Sheeran, Jennifer Lopez for upcoming album|date=January 17, 2020|work=CBC News|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/news/bryan-adams-jennifer-lopez-duet/|title=Bryan Adams Shares Duet With Jennifer Lopez, 'That's How Strong Our Love Is'|first=Laura|last=Stavropoulos|date=February 15, 2019|work=[[Universal Music Group]]|access-date=December 7, 2020}}</ref> The album debuted at number one on the [[Canadian Albums Chart]],<ref name="FYI">{{cite web|url=https://www.fyimusicnews.ca/articles/2019/03/11/bryan-adams-back-top-shine-light-debuting-no-1|title=Bryan Adams Is Back On Top With Shine A Light Debuting At No. 1|work=FYIMusicNews|date=March 11, 2019|access-date=December 1, 2020}}</ref> in the first week of its release, with 44,000 copies sold; its previous number one in Canada going back to the ''[[Tracks of My Years]]'' album released in October 2014. This was his 11th album in the top ten and the fifth album at the top of the Canadian charts.<ref name="FYI" /> It reached the second position in the [[UK Albums Chart]],<ref name="Official Chart">{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/17982/bryan-adams/|title=Bryan Adams full Official Chart|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|access-date=December 1, 2020}}</ref> and it was his tenth album to enter the UK Top-10 albums chart.<ref name="Official Chart" /> It also debuted in second position in [[Swiss Hitparade|Switzerland]], which was his 15th album to enter the top ten of the Swiss charts;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://swisscharts.com/album/Bryan-Adams/Shine-A-Light-376891|title= Swisscharts.com – Bryan Adams – Shine a Light|publisher=[[Swiss Hitparade]]|access-date=December 1, 2020}}</ref> second position in [[Ö3 Austria Top 40|Austria]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://austriancharts.at/charts/alben/15-03-2019|title=Austria Top 40 Alben 15.03.2019|publisher=[[Ö3 Austria Top 40]]|access-date=December 1, 2020}}</ref> second position in the [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|New Zealand]] charts; and the third position in [[GfK Entertainment charts|Germany]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://charts.nz/search.asp?cat=a&artist=bryan+adams&artist_search=starts&title=shine+a+light&title_search=starts|title=Official New Zealand Music Chart Bryan Adams Shine A Light 11/03/2019|publisher=[[Official New Zealand Music Chart]]|access-date=December 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/album-details-376891|title=Offizielle Deutsche Charts Bryan Adams Shine a Light|publisher=[[GfK Entertainment charts]]|access-date=December 1, 2020}}</ref>
Shine a Light was certified gold in Canada,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://musiccanada.com/gold-platinum/?_gp_search=Shine+a+Light%20Bryan+Adams|title=Canadian album certifications – Bryan Adams – Shine a Light|date= March 12, 2019|publisher=[[Music Canada]]|access-date=December 1, 2020}}</ref> and it won the [[Juno Award]] for "Best Adult Contemporary Album" in 2020.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/9411348/juno-awards-2020-winners-list|title=Here Are All the Winners From the 2020 Juno Awards|first=Denise|last=Warner|date=June 29, 2020|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=December 1, 2020}}</ref> On June 19, 2020, on the 155th anniversary of the end of [[Slavery in the United States]], the unreleased solo version of "[[Never Gonna Break My Faith]]" by [[Aretha Franklin]] was released with the participation of [[RCA Records]], [[RCA Inspiration]] and [[Legacy Recordings]], featuring a music video that contained contemporary topics, including films about [[George Floyd]] and the [[Black Lives Matter]] movement.<ref name="Rolling Stone">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/aretha-franklin-never-gonna-break-my-faith-solo-version-1017873/|title=Hear Aretha Franklin's Previously Unreleased Solo Version of 'Never Gonna Break My Faith'|first=Althea|last=Legaspi|date=June 19, 2020|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=December 9, 2020}}</ref>

Adams, while writing this song, did not think it would be performed by Aretha. He conceived something like a hymn and "so that it can express a sense of faith, and that even if you have lost something, there will always be an inner light to guide you." However, then Adams said:<blockquote>"When the song was ready, I told the producers that Aretha was going to sing it – and she did. This solo version had been on my computer for years (about 15 years), and when I heard that the creative director of Sony Music, longtime producer and friend of Aretha's Clive Davis, was making a movie about his life, I sent him this version. The world hadn't heard her full performance yet and it really needed to be heard. I'm so glad it's being released, the world needs this right now."<ref name="Rolling Stone" /></blockquote>
[[File:B.A. 2022.png|thumb|upright=0.75|Adams during the "So Happy It Hurts Tour 2022" at the [[Hallenstadion]] in Zurich]]
Adams was among hundreds of artists whose material was destroyed in the [[2008 Universal fire]].<ref name="Rosen2">{{cite news|last1=Rosen|first1=Jody|title=Here Are Hundreds More Artists Whose Tapes Were Destroyed in the UMG Fire|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/25/magazine/universal-music-fire-bands-list-umg.html|website=The New York Times|access-date=June 28, 2019|date=June 25, 2019}}</ref> Adams told the ''Times'' that he had asked Universal for access to the master tapes for ''Reckless'' in 2013 while working on a remastered edition of the album, but had been told that the tapes could not be found.<ref name="Rosen2" /> Adams eventually located a safety copy of the album to use on the remaster, and was not made aware of the fire until the ''Times''' initial report on June 1.<ref name="Rosen2" /> On November 15, 2019, Adams released an [[Extended play|EP]] dedicated to Christmas. The ''Christmas EP'' contains five tracks, the new track "[[Joe and Mary]]" and three previously released tracks: "[[Christmas Time (Bryan Adams song)|Christmas Time]]", "Reggae Christmas" and "Merry Christmas"; and a new interpretation of "[[Must Be Santa (song)|Must Be Santa]]", a 1960s Christmas song, performed in 2009 by [[Bob Dylan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://americansongwriter.com/bryan-adams-releases-christmas-ep-titled-christmas-ep/|title=Bryan Adams Releases Christmas EP, titled 'Christmas EP'|date=November 18, 2019|publisher=[[American Songwriter]]|access-date=December 1, 2020}}</ref> At the end of November 2019, the album [[The Christmas Present]] by the British singer-songwriter [[Robbie Williams]] is released, Adams participates in the duet with Williams in the song [[Christmas (Baby Please Come Home)]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thebreeze.co.nz/home/music/2019/11/robbie-williams-releases-his-first-original-christmas-song-from-.html|title=Robbie Williams releases his epic duet with Bryan Adams for his new Christmas album|date=November 14, 2019|publisher=[[The Breeze (New Zealand radio station)|The Breeze]]|access-date=December 1, 2020}}</ref>

=== 2020s ===
On November 13, 2020, Adams was featured on "[[Stop Crying Your Heart Out#BBC Radio 2 Allstars charity single|Stop Crying Your Heart Out]]" as part of the BBC Radio 2's Allstars' [[Children in Need]] charity single.<ref>{{Cite web|title=All-star BBC Children in Need charity single announced|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/bbc-radio-2s-allstars-including-cher-kylie-and-robbie-williams-to-release-stop-crying-your-heart-out-cover-for-bbc-children-in-need__31577/|access-date=November 13, 2020|website=www.officialcharts.com|language=en}}</ref> The single debuted at number seven on the Official UK Singles Chart<ref>{{Cite web|title=Official Singles Chart top ten0 – 20 November 2020 – 26 November 2020|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-chart/|access-date=November 20, 2020|website=www.officialcharts.com|language=en}}</ref> and number one on both the Official UK Singles Sales Chart and the Official UK Singles Download Chart.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Official Singles Sales Chart top ten0 – 20 November 2020 – 26 November 2020|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-sales-chart/|access-date=November 20, 2020|website=www.officialcharts.com|language=en}}</ref> On December 7, 2020, Adams announced a series of [[United Kingdom|UK]] concerts following the long hiatus of the "Shine a Light Tour" caused by the [[COVID-19 pandemic]] and the cancellation of a sold out 17-date tour with [[Bon Jovi]] in [[United States|US]] arenas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bonjovi.com/blogs/news/bon-jovi-2020-tour-announcement|title=Bon Jovi 2020 Tour Announcement|date=January 15, 2020|work=bonjovi.com|access-date=December 7, 2020}}</ref>

In July 2021, Adams signed a deal with Bertelsmann Music Group (BMG) to release his next album.<ref>{{Cite magazine|title=Bryan Adams Signs With BMG in First New Label Deal in 40-Plus Years|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/record-labels/9607365/bryan-adams-bmg-label-recording-deal/|first=Marc|last=Schneider|date=July 28, 2021|access-date=July 28, 2021|magazine=Billboard}}</ref>

On October 11, 2021, Adams released the title track of his 15th studio album, ''[[So Happy It Hurts]]''. The album was released in March 2022. Adams also announced dates for a worldwide tour starting in February 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Bryan Adams announces 2022 UK tour in support of new album 'So Happy It Hurts'|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/bryan-adams-announces-2022-uk-tour-in-support-of-new-album-so-happy-it-hurts-3067390|first=Charlotte|last=Krol|date=October 11, 2021|access-date=October 12, 2021|website=NME}}</ref>

On December 17, 2021, Adams announced the cancellation of all remaining tours and concerts for the year, including his New Year's Eve show in [[Vancouver]], due to both concerns and restrictions due to the [[SARS-CoV-2 Omicron variant]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ali |first1=Amir |title=Bryan Adams Vancouver New Year's show cancelled over Omicron concerns |url=https://dailyhive.com/vancouver/bryan-adams-new-years-eve-vancouver-concert-cancelled-omicron |access-date=December 18, 2021 |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |issue=Daily Hive |date=December 17, 2021}}</ref>

On February 15, 2022, through his official [[instagram]] profile, he announced the publication on his official [[YouTube]] channel of new versions of the 16 songs of ''[[Pretty Woman: The Musical]]'' sung by Adams himself, the songs were co-written by Adams and [[Jim Vallance]], after the release of the album recorded by the cast of the musical in the October 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/VIDEOS-Bryan-Adams-Sings-the-Songs-of-PRETTY-WOMAN-THE-MUSICAL-20220218|title=VIDEOS: Bryan Adams Sings the Songs of PRETTY WOMAN THE MUSICAL|author=Stephi Wild|date=February 18, 2022|website=broadwayworld.com|access-date=February 18, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2018/8/9/pretty-woman-the-musical-soundtrack-with-songs-written-by-br.html|title="Pretty Woman: The Musical" soundtrack, with songs written by Bryan Adams, coming next month|publisher=[[ABC NewsRadio]]|access-date=February 17, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLaPEstx8t-dofPPewobx9SRVFJHTUVJH5|title=Bryan Adams Pretty Woman - The Musical|website=youtube.com}}</ref>

On April 1, 2022, Adams released ''Classic'', an album of reworked and reimagined hits.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Graff |first=Gary |last2=Clevel |first2=Special to |last3=.com |date=2022-03-07 |title=Bryan Adams talks missed Rock Hall inductions, lockdown creative spark, new album & more |url=https://www.cleveland.com/entertainment/2022/03/bryan-adams-talks-covid-missed-rock-hall-inductions-new-album-more.html |access-date=2022-04-01 |website=cleveland |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=McCabe |first=Kathy |date=March 26, 2022 |title=Bryan Adams: why the famous Canadian rocker has ‘done a Taylor Swift’ |url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/music/bryan-adams-why-the-famous-canadian-rocker-has-done-a-taylor-swift/news-story/3e700441905deb9297baf4b00b019d77 |url-status=live |website=www.dailytelegraph.com.au}}</ref> This was followed on July 29, 2022, with ''Classic Pt II''.

== ''Pretty Woman: The Musical'' ==
Adams approached [[Disney]] in 2009 to see if they would be interested in making the 1990 film into ''[[Pretty Woman: The Musical]]'' for Broadway. But it wasn't until seven years later that he re-approached them and was introduced to producer [[Paula Wagner]] who put him together with director [[Jerry Mitchell]]. Adams recruited [[Jim Vallance]], and the two of them spent the next two years writing the music and lyrics, and completed the songs in March 2018. The musical made its debut on Broadway in August 2018 and opened in London's West End on February 13, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.atgtickets.com/shows/pretty-woman-the-musical/piccadilly-theatre/|title=Pretty Woman The Musical – Piccadilly Theatre|website=Atgtickets.com|date=February 13, 2020|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>

== Artistry ==
=== Voice and timbre ===
{{Main|List of tenors in non-classical music}}
{{quote box|align=right|width=25em|quote="When I think of Bryan Adams, I think of a great storyteller who writes the kind of songs that make me want to sing.
Known for his killer, gritty voice, Bryan is a t-shirt and blue jeans guy who wrote some truly unforgettable melodies.|source= — Matt Williams, of [[Ken Tamplin]] Vocal Academy in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kentamplinvocalacademy.com/2020/06/what-makes-this-singer-great-bryan-adams/|title=What Makes This Singer Great? Bryan Adams|first=Matt|last=Williams|date=30 June 2020|website=kentamplinvocalacademy.com|access-date=10 December 2020}}</ref>}} Gifted with a powerful hoarse voice, with a particularly recognizable [[timbre]], Bryan Adams began his career in the mid-1970s, taking over from original singer Nick Gilder of [[Sweeney Todd (band)|Sweeney Todd]], when he was a teenager and had a youthful voice very far from the standards he has achieved over the years. With [[Jim Vallance|Vallance]]'s help, it wasn't long before Adams established a powerful and distinct sound, compared to that of [[Joe Elliott]], [[Rod Stewart]], [[Paul Rodgers]] and [[Steve Marriott]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Bryan-Adams|title=Bryan Adams Canadian musician and photographer|first=Austin|last=Mardon|publisher=britannica.com|access-date=November 30, 2020}}</ref> Adams' voice is often taken as an example of comparing similarities between different singers [[Rod Stewart]], [[Joe Cocker]], [[Richard Marx]] and [[Don Henley]]. Recognized as one of rock's greatest performers, he is considered among the best live singers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bryan Adams Works Hard To Please, Succeeds More Often Than Not|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1992-04-29-9202070910-story.html|first=Greg|last=Kot|date=April 29, 1992|access-date=December 10, 2020|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://entertainment.inquirer.net/213378/bryan-adams-57-sounded-good-record|title=Bryan Adams at 57 sounded as good as he did on record|work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|date=January 24, 2017|access-date=December 10, 2020|first=Allan|last=Policarpio}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/sep/11/concert-review-bryan-adams-rocks-wolf-trap-despite/|title=Adams plays straight from the heart at balmy Wolf Trap show|work=[[The Washington Times]]|date=September 11, 2016|access-date=December 10, 2020|first=Eric|last=Althoff}}</ref>

=== Musical style ===
Adams has played various styles of rock, from [[hard rock]] and [[arena rock]] to [[pop rock]] and [[soft rock]]. During the first few years of his career in the 1970s Adams fronted [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[glam rock]] band [[Sweeney Todd (band)|Sweeney Todd]]; the band played [[hard rock]] as well as [[glam rock]].<ref name="Sweeney Todd" /> His early songs were about kids and about the lives of young people, and he is known for his romantic [[Sentimental ballad#Power ballads|ballads]]. Adams has never shied away from political or social commentary, especially with songs such as "Native Son" and "Remembrance Day" from the album ''[[Into the Fire (album)|Into the Fire]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/albums-folder/pg-album-adams-05-into.html|title=Into the Fire by Bryan Adams|work=jimvallance.com|access-date=December 6, 2020|archive-date=May 7, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140507031658/http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/albums-folder/pg-album-adams-05-into.html|url-status=dead}}</ref> "Don't Drop That Bomb on Me" from ''[[Waking Up the Neighbours]],'' and "Ultimate Love" from ''[[Ultimate (Bryan Adams album)|Ultimate]]''. In 1978, after meeting with the drummer and main songwriter [[Jim Vallance]] for Canadian [[rock music|rock]] band [[Prism (band)|Prism]] under the pseudonym "Rodney Higgs",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/albums-folder/pg-album-prism-01-prism.html|title= History of Prism, Jim Vallance Discography|work=jimvallance.com|access-date=December 6, 2020}}</ref> the initial course was quite difficult. Demos of Adams' early songs were rejected by numerous record companies.

In 1978, the Adams–Vallance duo managed to sign their record deal with [[A&M Records]] and released the single "[[Let Me Take You Dancing]]". It is notable for being Adams' first solo single and his first-ever release as a solo artist, when he was 19.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/songs-folder-may-27/pg-song-adams-let-me-take.html|title=Let Me Take You Dancing by Bryan Adams|work=jimvallance.com|access-date=December 6, 2020}}</ref> The genre of the single was [[disco]]; the melody, a piano riff inspired by [[Robbie King (musician)|Robbie King]], was composed by Vallance on his parents' piano during the Christmas holidays in 1977; Adams, meanwhile, helped turn the riff into a song. In 1982, Vallance and Adams received a call from producer Michael James Jackson to contribute some songs for the next [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]] album. Although Vallance and Adams were not fans of [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]], it was a golden opportunity for exposure for their songs by a world-class rock group. In collaboration with [[Gene Simmons]], the track "War Machine" and a rewrite "Rock 'n Roll Hell" were recorded by Kiss for the album ''[[Creatures of the Night]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/songs-folder-may-27/pg-song-kiss-war-machine.html|title=War Machine by Kiss|work=jimvallance.com|access-date=December 6, 2020}}</ref> Adams' first solo albums, ''[[Bryan Adams (album)|Bryan Adams]]'' and ''[[You Want It You Got It]]'', two clear-cut [[Rock music|rock]] and [[hard rock]] albums, respectively, indicated the styles that Adams would become famous for.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/albums-folder/pg-album-adams-02-you.html|title=You Want It You Got It by Bryan Adams|work=jimvallance.com|access-date=December 6, 2020|archive-date=November 2, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151102013945/http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/albums-folder/pg-album-adams-02-you.html|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1983, with the release of ''[[Cuts Like a Knife]]'', ''[[Reckless (Bryan Adams album)|Reckless]]'' and ''[[Into the Fire (album)|Into the Fire]]'', their music was characterized by being hard rock with melodic overtones and powerful ballads (known as power ballads); the production of the first five albums was in cooperation with the American [[record producer]] [[Bob Clearmountain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/albums-folder/pg-album-adams-04-reck.html|title=Reckless by Bryan Adams|work=jimvallance.com|access-date=December 6, 2020|archive-date=September 29, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100929130849/http://jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/albums-folder/pg-album-adams-04-reck.html|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mixthis.com/discography|title=Work in Progress... (many records not yet listed)|work=mixthis.com|access-date=December 7, 2020}}</ref>

In the 1990s, with the release of ''Waking Up the Neighbours'' in 1991, produced by [[Robert John "Mutt" Lange]], they left the hard rock sound and released an album closer to classic rock and roll, taking inspiration from the sounds of bands and artists such as [[Def Leppard]] and [[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/albums-folder/pg-album-adams-07-wak.html|title=Waking Up the Neighbors by Bryan Adams|work=jimvallance.com|access-date=December 6, 2020|archive-date=June 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200614183826/http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/albums-folder/pg-album-adams-07-wak.html|url-status=dead}}</ref> This album is based on these tones, which brings out a leap in notoriety and also in musical quality to the Canadian rocker, placing itself right in the middle between the sounds of and those of "18 Til 'I Die". Without forgetting that just after "Wakin 'up the Neighbors" will come the best ''[[So Far So Good (Bryan Adams album)|So Far So Good]]'', assisted by this album, which churns out some of the singles that Adams fans.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ultimateclassicrock.com/bryan-adams-waking-up-the-neighbours/|title=HOW BRYAN ADAMS REBOUNDED WITH 'WAKING UP THE NEIGHBOURS'|first=Jeff|last=Giles|date=September 23, 2016|work=ultimateclassicrock.com|access-date=December 6, 2020}}</ref> In 1996, with his album ''[[18 til I Die]]'', Adams and Lange adopted a pop rock sound more in line with the style of the time. Many ballads were included in this work, although it also contained some rock songs such as "[[18 til I Die (song)|18 til I Die]]" and "[[The Only Thing That Looks Good on Me Is You]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://victor-li.com/bryanadams/|title=Career Killers: "18 'Til I Die" by Bryan Adams|first=Victor|last=Li|date=February 21, 2020|work=victor-li.com|access-date=December 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,292826,00.html|title=Entertainment Weekly review|website=Ew.com|access-date=July 14, 2021|archive-date=September 5, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140905060020/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,292826,00.html|url-status=dead}}</ref> The album sees the collaboration of the American singer and songwriter [[Gretchen Peters]], still active today. In 1998, ''[[On a Day Like Today (album)|On a Day Like Today]]'' was released, co-produced by his compatriot [[Bob Rock]], he opted for a sound oriented to [[pop rock]], heavily influenced by contemporary bands.

Upon their return in 2000 with the album ''[[Room Service (Bryan Adams album)|Room Service]]'', Adams produced the album and co-wrote the songs with various co-writers, the themes of the songs being varied between street life, touring, truth, love and relationships. He again opted for a rock-oriented sound. In 2008, with ''[[11 (Bryan Adams album)|11]]'', produced by the same Adams with the collaboration of Mutt lange, he sees the return of his long-time collaborator [[Jim Vallance]] after more than 15 years, he has experienced a sound softer, combining songs from [[soft rock]], [[pop rock]] and melodic rock.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimvallance.com/01-music-folder/albums-folder/pg-album-adams-13-eleven.html|title=11 by Bryan Adams|work=jimvallance.com|access-date=December 6, 2020}}</ref> With ''[[Get Up (Bryan Adams album)|Get Up]]'' produced entirely by [[Jeff Lynne]], they continued in the line of rock, with the strong influence of Lynne's fifty-year experience.<ref>{{cite magazine|
language=de|url=http://www.rollingstone.de/reviews/bryan-adams-get-up|title=Bryan Adams Get Up , reviews|first=Jörn|last= Schlüter|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] Germany|date=October 16, 2015|access-date=December 6, 2020}}</ref> In 2019, with ''[[Shine a Light (Bryan Adams album)|Shine a Light]]'', he combined [[Rock music|rock]] with [[pop rock]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/news/bryan-adams-shine-a-light/|title=NEWS Bryan Adams Shares New Song 'Shine A Light' Co-Written With Ed Sheeran|first= Tim|last= Peacock|date=January 17, 2019|work=[[Universal Music Group]]|access-date=December 7, 2020}}</ref>

=== Influences and favourite musicians ===
{{quote box|align=right|width=25em|quote="If I were to record the songs that were the real influences in my life, I would record a lot of hard rock from the 70s, "says Adams. "And most of those songs are untouchable. There are many reasons why I wanted to pick up a guitar," says Adams. "One of them was the ''[[Machine Head (album)|Machine Head]]'' album, by [[Ritchie Blackmore]] and [[Deep Purple]]".|source= —Bryan Adams, in 2014.<ref name="The Globe and Mail">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/music/tracking-bryan-adamss-years-of-influences-in-his-new-album/article21386119/|title=Tracking Bryan Adams's years of influences in his new album|first=Brad|last=Wheeler|date=30 October 2014|journal=[[The Globe and Mail]]|access-date=30 November 2020}}</ref>}} Among his youthful influences, the musician has often mentioned [[Elvis Presley]] and [[Bob Dylan]] as well as all the pop and rock heard as a boy on the radio. While making the album [[cover version]] ''[[Tracks of My Years]]'', the album was released in 2014, Adams in an interview published by the Canadian newspaper [[The Globe and Mail]], Adams said the real influences in my life, I would record a lot of [[hard rock]] from the 1970s. According to Adams, most of those songs are untouchable.<ref name="The Globe and Mail" />

His main sources of inspiration also include guitarists, besides Blackmore, he was influenced by guitarists such as [[Jimmy Page]], [[Eric Clapton]], [[Mick Ronson]], [[Jeff Beck]], [[Peter Frampton]] and [[Eddie Van Halen]]. Other influential and favourite artists were [[Alice Cooper]], [[Black Sabbath]], [[Humble Pie]], [[Bob Marley]], [[Bob Seger]], [[Chuck Berry]], [[David Bowie]], [[Jackie Wilson]], [[Joe Cocker]], [[John Lennon]], [[Led Zeppelin]], [[Leonard Cohen]], [[Ray Charles]], [[Sam Cooke]], [[The Beatles]], [[The Who]], [[The Beach Boys]], [[The Rolling Stones]] and [[Van Morrison]].<ref name="The Globe and Mail" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guitarworld.com/features/bryan-adams-i-realized-i-had-made-it-when-i-could-pay-my-rent-for-more-than-a-month-without-relying-on-anyone|title=Bryan Adams: "I realized I had made it when I could pay my rent for more than a month without relying on anyone"|first=James|last=Wood|date=April 28, 2020|publisher=guitarworld.com|access-date=November 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/mar/17/theplaylist|title=Liked by Bryan|first=Rosie|last=Swash|date=March 11, 2008|work=[[TheGuardian.com]]|access-date=January 12, 2021}}</ref>

== Impact and legacy ==
With the mainstream success of ''Reckless'' in the 1980s, five times multi-platinum "Album of the Year" and in the top 20 in "The Best AOR Albums Of All Time" according to ''[[Kerrang!]]'' Magazine,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/kerrang.html#1985|title=Kerrang! End Of Year Lists|publisher=rocklistmusic.co.uk|access-date=January 15, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/kerrang_p2.htm#AOR|title=The Best AOR Albums Of All Time|date=October 29, 1988|publisher=rocklistmusic.co.uk|access-date=January 15, 2021}}</ref> the true masterpiece of the Canadian rocker according to the Italian magazine ''[[Panorama (magazine)|Panorama]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.panorama.it/lifestyle/Musica/bryan-adams-reckless-iostoacasa|title=L'album del giorno: Bryan Adams, Reckless|first=Gabriele|last=Antonucci|date=March 20, 2020|publisher=[[Panorama (magazine)|Panorama]]|language=it|access-date=January 15, 2021}}</ref> and ''Waking Up The Neighbors'' in the 1990s, having gained worldwide circulation, Adams' impact still persists today. Being one of the most popular rock artists of the 80s and 90s, the merit of having maintained a pure rock at that time as the world went into [[Hip hop music]] and [[Electronic music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/nov/26/bryan-adams-review-rock|title=Bryan Adams review – clinically dispatched hits still thrill the masses|first=Dave|last=Simpson|date=November 26, 2014|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=January 15, 2021}}</ref>

Referred to as the "Groover From Vancouver",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://planetradio.co.uk/magic/entertainment/music/bryan-adams/|title=Bryan Adams: How the 'Groover From Vancouver' became famous|date=August 9, 2020|work=[[Magic (UK radio station)]]|publisher=planetradio.co.uk|access-date=January 15, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/bryan-adams-hit-was-about-sex-not-1969/|title=Bryan Adams: Hit Was About Sex, Not 1969|date=September 8, 2008|work=[[CBS News]]|access-date=January 15, 2021}}</ref> he is known for his powerful rock songs and romantic ballads, and his music has appeared in dozens of films both as a singer and as a songwriter and co-writer since the early 1980s, including ''[[Class (film)|Class]]'', ''[[A Night in Heaven]]'', ''[[Real Genius]]'', ''[[Renegades (1989 film)|Renegades]]'', ''[[Pink Cadillac (film)|Pink Cadillac]]'', ''[[An Innocent Man (film)|An Innocent Man]]'', ''[[Problem Child 2]]'', ''[[Robin Hood: Prince of Thieves]]'', ''[[The Cutting Edge]]'', ''[[The Three Musketeers (1993 film)|The Three Musketeers]]'', ''[[Don Juan DeMarco]]'', ''[[The Mirror Has Two Faces]]'', ''[[Jack (1996 film)|Jack]]'', ''[[Red Corner]]'', ''[[Hope Floats]]'', ''[[Spirit: Stallion of the Cimarron]]'', ''[[House of Fools (film)|House of Fools]]'', ''[[Devil's Gate (2004 film)|Devil's Gate]]'', ''[[Racing Stripes]]'', ''[[Color Me Kubrick]]'', ''[[The Guardian (2006 film)|The Guardian]]'', ''[[Bobby (2006 film)|Bobby]]'', ''[[Cashback (film)|Cashback]]'', ''[[Bridge to Terabithia (2007 film)|Bridge to Terabithia]]'', ''[[Old Dogs (film)|Old Dogs]]'', ''[[Jock the Hero Dog]]'' and ''[[Legends of Oz: Dorothy's Return]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/culture/examining-the-many-movie-songs-of-bryan-adams/|title=Examining the Many Movie Songs of Bryan Adams|first= Paul|last=Childs|publisher=[[Den of Geek]]|date=February 12, 2018|access-date=January 15, 2021}}</ref>

== Activism and humanitarian work ==

=== Humanitarian work ===
Most of Adams's philanthropic activity is through The Bryan Adams Foundation, which "aims to improve the quality of people's lives around the world by providing financial grants to support specific projects that are committed to bettering the lives of other people".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebryanadamsfoundation.com/index.php?target=aboutus|title=About Us|access-date=August 10, 2019}}</ref> The foundation is mostly funded by Adams himself.

Since the 1980s, Adams has participated in concerts and other activities to help raise money and awareness for a variety of causes. His first high-profile charity appearance came in 1985 when he opened the US transmission of [[Live Aid]] from Philadelphia.<ref name="1985: Was Live Aid the best rock concert ever?">{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/witness/july/13/newsid_3041000/3041494.stm
|title=1985: Was Live Aid the best rock concert ever?
|work=BBC News
|access-date=January 29, 2006|date= July 13, 1985}}</ref> In June of the next year, Adams participated in the two-week [[Amnesty International]] "A Conspiracy of Hope" tour alongside [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], U2 and [[Peter Gabriel]].<ref name="1985: Was Live Aid the best rock concert ever?" /> In 1986, Adams performed at The Prince's Trust All-Star Rock Concert in Wembley Arena to celebrate first 10 years of the Trust and again in June 1987 at the 5th Annual [[Prince's Trust]] Rock Gala along with [[Elton John]], [[George Harrison]], [[Ringo Starr]] and others. The following year on June 11, 1988, Adams performed at the [[Nelson Mandela]] birthday party concert at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gettyimages.ca/detail/news-photo/photo-of-bryan-adams-bryan-adams-performing-on-stage-at-the-news-photo/86099071|title=Photo of Bryan ADAMS, Bryan Adams performing on stage at the Nelson...|website=Getty Images|language=en-gb|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> In June 1988, [[East Berlin]] experienced a lavish rock'n'roll festival called ''Peace Concert'': Adams and [[Joe Cocker]] played in [[Weissensee (Berlin)|Weißensee]] in front of a crowd of over 85,000 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mdr.de/zeitreise/bryan-adams-104.html|title=Konzert von Bryan Adams im Rahmen der Friedenswoche der Berliner Jugend auf der Radrennbahn in Berlin-Weißensee, Ostberlin, DDR|date=June 1988|publisher=mdr.de|language=de|access-date=November 27, 2020}}</ref><ref name="Rocksommer der DDR">{{cite web|url=https://www.welt.de/kultur/musik/gallery118177462/Der-legendaere-Rocksommer-der-DDR.html|title=Der legendäre Rocksommer der DDR|date=June 1988|publisher=welt.de|language=de|access-date=November 27, 2020}}</ref> Only a week later, [[David Bowie]] played music in front of the [[Reichstag building]], in front of 60,000 fans.<ref name="Rocksommer der DDR" /> While [[Pink Floyd]] and [[Michael Jackson]] were in front of the [[Bundestag]], with 40,000 people to attend the concert,<ref name="Rocksommer der DDR" /> [[Bruce Springsteen]] performed in front of a crowd of over 160,000 people.<ref name="Rocksommer der DDR" />

In March 1989, he performed on the [[Greenpeace]] album ''Rainbow Warriors'', which was also released in the [[Soviet Union]] on the [[Melodiya]] label. According to Greenpeace, worldwide sales raised more than eight million dollars for Greenpeace initiatives.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.u2songs.com/discography/various_artists_greenpeace_rainbow_warriors_breakthrough_album|title="Greenpeace: Rainbow Warriors" – Various Artists|website=u2songs.com|access-date=November 30, 2020}}</ref> Highlights of the set include ''[[Somebody (Bryan Adams song)|Somebody]]'' by Bryan Adams, a live version of ''[[Pride (In the Name of Love)]]'' by [[U2]] and the hits by [[The Pretenders]], [[R.E.M.]], [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], [[Grateful Dead]], [[Thompson Twins]], [[Peter Gabriel]] and [[Dire Straits]].<ref name="Greenpeace Rainbow Warriors">{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/it/Various-Greenpeace-Rainbow-Warriors/master/99221|title=Greenpeace Rainbow Warriors|website=[[Discogs]]|access-date=November 30, 2020}}</ref>

In July 1989, Adams committed to work on another charity record: the remake of the [[Deep Purple]] classic "[[Smoke on the Water]]" for ''[[Rock Aid Armenia]]'' to obtain funds for the [[1988 Armenian earthquake|earthquake]] that occurred in [[Armenia]] at that time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loudersound.com/features/rock-aid-armenia-how-the-ultimate-version-of-smoke-on-the-water-was-recorded|title=Rock Aid Armenia: how the ultimate version of Smoke On The Water was recorded|last=Everley|first= Dave|date=February 5, 2020|website=loudersound.com|access-date=November 26, 2020}}</ref> Adams helped commemorate the fall of the [[Berlin Wall]] when, in 1990, he joined many other guests (including his songwriting partner [[Michael Kamen]]) for [[Roger Waters]]' [[The Wall – Live in Berlin|massive performance]] of ''[[The Wall]]'' in Berlin, Germany.<ref name="Pink Floyd – The Wall">{{cite web
|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/h2g2/A5907332
|title=Pink Floyd – The Wall
|publisher=BBC
|work =h2g2
|access-date=January 29, 2006}}</ref> He performed the [[Pink Floyd]] songs "What Shall We Do Now?" and "[[Young Lust (song)|Young Lust]]" during the performance of ''The Wall'', and then joined Waters, [[Joni Mitchell]], [[Cyndi Lauper]], [[Van Morrison]], [[Paul Carrack]] and others to perform Waters' "[[The Tide Is Turning]]" to close the concert.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jonimitchell.com/library/video.cfm?id=186|title=Joni Mitchell – The Tide Is Turning – video|website=www.jonimitchell.com|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> On March 2, 1993, Adams attended the [[Rock for the Rainforest]], [[benefit concert]] hosted by [[Rainforest Foundation Fund]] is a [[charitable foundation]] founded in 1987 and dedicated to the focus on [[rainforest]]s and defend [[indigenous rights|rights]] of the [[indigenous peoples]] who live there. hosted by [[Sting (musician)|Sting]] and his wife [[Trudie Styler]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/1993/03/04/tina-dustin-sting-coro-per-amazzonia.html|title=Tina, Dustin, Sting coro per l'AmazzoniaT|date=March 4, 1993|last=Porro|first=Gabriele|publisher=[[la Repubblica]]|language=it|access-date=November 27, 2020}}</ref> The event, which took place at [[Carnegie Hall]] in [[New York City]], was attended by Sting, [[Tina Turner]], [[James Taylor]], [[George Michael]], [[Tom Jones (singer)|Tom Jones]] and [[Dustin Hoffman]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-world-of-tina.com/rainforest---concert.html|title=Rainforest (1993)|date=March 2, 1993|publisher=the-world-of-tina.com|language=en-US|access-date=November 27, 2020}}</ref> $800,000 was raised for the evening.<ref>''Press Association''. March 2, 1993. "Sting Sings."</ref> On April 24, 1993, he participated in the benefit concert [[Farm Aid]] at the [[Jack Trice Stadium]] in [[Ames, Iowa|Ames]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.farmaid.org/site/c.qlI5IhNVJsE/b.2723673/k.8C39/Past_Concerts.htm|title=Past Concerts – Farm Aid (April 24, 1993 Ames, Iowa)|publisher=[[Farm Aid]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523191508/http://www.farmaid.org/site/c.qlI5IhNVJsE/b.2723673/k.8C39/Past_Concerts.htm|access-date=December 2, 2020|archive-date=May 23, 2011}}</ref>

On December 10, 1997, Adams took part in a concert, "A Gift of Song : A Concert To Benefit The Children Of The World", in celebration of the US Committee for [[UNICEF]] 50th Anniversary, held at the Z-100 Jingle Ball Madison Square Garden in [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celinedionweb.com/en/event/a-gift-song-concert/|title='A Gift of Song' Concert (USA)|website=CelineDionWeb.com|access-date=December 9, 2020}}</ref>

On January 29, 2005, Adams joined the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]] benefit concert in [[Toronto]] for victims of the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake]]. Twenty years after performing at Live Aid in the US, Adams played at Canada's [[Live 8 concert, Barrie|Live 8 show in Barrie]], Ontario.<ref name="Reach Out to Asia" /> Later that year, he performed in Qatar and raised GB£1.5M (US$2,617,000) from the concert. He also auctioned a white Fender Stratocaster guitar signed by many{{how many|date=December 2017}} of the world's prominent{{according to whom|date=December 2017}} guitarists. The guitar raised a total of US$3.7 million for charity and thus set a record as the world's costliest guitar.<ref name="Reach Out to Asia" /> The money went to Qatar's "Reach Out to Asia" campaign to help the underprivileged across the continent.<ref name="Reach Out to Asia">{{cite web
|url=http://www.qf.edu.qa/output/page1099.asp
|title=Reach Out to Asia
|publisher=Qatar Foundation
|access-date=January 29, 2006|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20060221111524/http://www.qf.edu.qa/output/page1099.asp <!-- Bot retrieved archive -->|archive-date = February 21, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news
|url=http://www.brain-damage.co.uk/archive/gilmour-signed-guitar-in-charity-auction.html
|title=Gilmour signed guitar in charity auction
|publisher=Brain Damage
|access-date=February 6, 2011|year=2006}}</ref> Money raised also went to some of his own projects like rebuilding a school in Thailand and building a new sports center in Sri Lanka, both of which had been devastated by the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake|Indian Ocean tsunami]].<ref name="Reach Out to Asia" />

On May 25, 2005, Adams raised £1.3M with cousin Johnny Armitage, from a concert and auction entitled Rock by the River for the [[Royal Marsden Hospital]] in London.<ref name="Bryan Adams rocks by the river">{{cite web
|url         = http://www.royalmarsden.nhs.uk/RMH/info/newsevents/pressreleases/pr24052005.htm
|title       = Bryan Adams rocks by the river
|publisher   = Royal Marsden NHS Foundation Trust
|access-date  = January 29, 2006
|url-status     = dead
|archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20061010162757/http://www.royalmarsden.nhs.uk/RMH/info/newsevents/pressreleases/pr24052005.htm
|archive-date = October 10, 2006
|df          = dmy-all
}}</ref> On May 15, 2006, Adams returned to London to attend the Hope Foundation's event (hosted by designer [[Bella Freud]]), helping to raise a portion of the £250,000 to support the [[Palestinian refugee]] children.<ref name="Charity">{{cite web|url=http://www.hopingfoundation.org/fundraising/RonnieScottsPR2.pdf|title=Ronnie Scotts|publisher=Hoping Foundation|access-date=January 29, 2006|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080908013941/http://www.hopingfoundation.org/fundraising/RonnieScottsPR2.pdf|archive-date=September 8, 2008}}</ref> The following June, he offered individuals from the public the chance to bid to sing with him live in concert at three different charity auctions in London. Over £50,000 was raised with money going to the [[NSPCC]], [[Children in Need]], and the [[University College Hospital]].<ref name="One Night Live" /> On February 28, 2008, he appeared in One Night Live at the [[Air Canada Centre]] in Toronto with [[Josh Groban]], [[Sarah McLachlan]], [[Jann Arden]], and [[RyanDan]] in aid of the [[Sunnybrook Health Sciences Centre|Sunnybrook Hospital]] Women and Babies Program.<ref name="One Night Live">{{cite web
|url=http://www.onenightlive.ca
|title=One Night Live
|work=Sunnybrook
|access-date=January 29, 2006
|archive-date=November 24, 2007
|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071124172719/http://www.onenightlive.ca/
|url-status=dead
}}</ref>

[[File:Badams.jpg|thumb|left|Adams in [[Karachi]], Pakistan]]
On January 29, 2006, Adams became the first Western artist to perform in [[Karachi, Pakistan]] after the [[September 11th attacks]] in conjunction with a benefit concert by [[Shehzad Roy]] to raise money for underprivileged children to go to school.<ref name="Bryan Adams performs to Karachi" /> Some of the proceeds of that concert also went to victims of the [[2005 Pakistan earthquake]].<ref name="Bryan Adams performs to Karachi">{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4659782.stm
|title=Bryan Adams performs to Karachi
|work=BBC News
|access-date=January 29, 2006|date=January 29, 2006}}</ref>

On October 18, 2007, Adams was billed to perform in [[Tel Aviv]] and [[Jericho]] as part of the [[OneVoice Movement]] concerts, hoping to aid in solving the [[Israeli–Palestinian conflict]].<ref name="Adams's peace concerts called off" /> The peace concert for supporters of a two-state solution to the conflict with Israel was called off because of security concerns.<ref name="Adams's peace concerts called off">{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7044614.stm
|title=Adams's peace concerts called off
|work=BBC News
|access-date=October 15, 2007|date=October 15, 2007}}</ref>

On January 13, 2010, he received the [[Allan Waters Humanitarian Award]] for participating in numerous concerts and charity campaigns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/bryan-adams-lands-juno-awards-humanitarian-honour-1.883922|title=Bryan Adams lands Juno Awards humanitarian honour|date=January 13, 2010|publisher=[[CBC.ca]]|access-date=November 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kingstonherald.com/entertainment/bryan-adams-award-2010314175|title=Bryan Adams to Receive Humanitarian Spirit Award At Canadian Music Week|last=Hart|first=Courtney|publisher=kingstonherald.com|date=February 2010|access-date=November 24, 2020}}</ref>

On January 13, 2011, he participated in the Concert for Killing Cancer at the [[Hammersmith Apollo]] in [[London]] together with the historic rock band [[The Who]], [[Jeff Beck]], [[Debbie Harry]], and [[Richard Ashcroft]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gear4music.com/news/article/Bryan-Adams-joins-KILLING-Cancer-concert/2UB/2010-11-12|title=Bryan Adams joins KILLING Cancer concert|publisher=Music Gear News|access-date=November 24, 2020}}</ref> On October 22, 2013, he attended the [[Tony Martell|TJ Martell Foundation's]] 38th Annual Honors Gala in [[New York City]] for [[Cancer Research]]. He performed alongside [[Sting (musician)|Sting]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2013/10/9/sting-bryan-adams-to-honor-mtv-co-founder-at-charity-gala.html|title=Sting & Bryan Adams to Honor MTV Co-Founder at Charity Gala|date=October 9, 2013|work=[[ABC News]]|access-date=November 24, 2020}}</ref>
{{quote box|align=right|width=25em|quote="Bryan's work – as a songwriter, composer, musician, recording artist, performer, and photographer – has touched millions of lives around the world. Add to that the countless number of causes and disadvantaged struggling around the world that his foundation has directly supported, protected and enriched – it's remarkable. My father and I couldn't be more proud of Bryan's benevolence, and it is our privilege to honour him with this year's Allan Slaight Humanitarian Spirit Award."|source= —Gary Slaight, 2015<ref name="Canadian Music Industry" />}}

On September 14, 2014, Adams was the first artist to sing at the [[Invictus Games]] organised by [[Prince Harry]] in East London. [[Prince Harry]] reciprocated by attending Adams's exhibition on Wounded soldiers in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/showbiz/news/a609618/prince-harry-attends-bryan-adamss-war-veterans-photo-exhibition.html|title=Prince Harry attends Bryan Adams's war veterans photo exhibition|work=Digital Spy|date=November 12, 2014}}</ref> Interviewed in November 2014 by ''KALTBLUT Magazine'', he presents his photo book ''Wounded: The Legacy of War'' then Adams said: <blockquote> "War is not the answer in solving problems. Sometimes, in 2004, George Bush said that "the world without Saddam Hussein's regime is a better and safer place, and as we have seen, nothing could be further from the truth. Millions of displaced people, hundreds of thousands of dead, and countless thousands of injured, physically or mentally. It is an unspeakable disaster, like the war in Afghanistan."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kaltblut-magazine.com/an-interview-bryan-adams-wounded-the-legacy-of-war/|title=An Interview: Bryan Adams! Wounded: The Legacy of War|first=Katerina|last=Kombercova|date=20 November 2014|work=kaltblut-magazine.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920231855/http://www.kaltblut-magazine.com/an-interview-bryan-adams-wounded-the-legacy-of-war/|access-date=11 December 2020|archive-date=20 September 2016}}</ref></blockquote>

In May 2015, he received the "Allan Slaight Humanitarian Spirit Award" in recognition of his social activism and support for various humanitarian causes, presented during Canadian Music Week at the ''Canadian Music Industry & Broadcast Awards Gala''.<ref name="Canadian Music Industry">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/6560903/canadian-music-industry-honors-bryan-adams-cowboy-junkies-warner-music|title=Canadian Music Industry Honors Bryan Adams, Cowboy Junkies, Warner Music Exec Steve Kane|date=May 8, 2015|last=Karen|first=Bliss|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|language=en-US|access-date=November 24, 2020}}</ref> In 2016, Adams canceled an April 14 concert at [[Mississippi Coast Coliseum]] in [[Biloxi, Mississippi|Biloxi]]. From July 1, the state implemented the law whereby religious groups and private companies can refuse to provide their services to [[Same-sex relationship|same-sex couples]]; after the example of [[Bruce Springsteen]], who canceled his show in [[Greensboro, North Carolina|Greensboro]], [[North Carolina]] in protest against the law prohibiting anti-discrimination measures against gays, lesbians, bisexuals and transgenders in using public restrooms, Adams also followed "the Boss".<ref name="Biloxi">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/apr/11/bryan-adams-cancels-mississippi-tour-date-protest-of-anti-lgbt-law|title=Bryan Adams cancels Mississippi tour dates in protest over anti-LGBT law|first=Nigel M|last=Smith|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=April 11, 2016|access-date=December 11, 2020}}</ref>
{{quote box
|align = left
|width = 25em
|quote="I cannot, in good conscience, perform in a state where some people are denied civil rights due to sexual orientation"
|source = —Bryan Adams cancels date of the "Get Up Tour" in Biloxi, Mississippi to protest the anti-[[LGBT]] law <ref name="Biloxi" />
}}
On September 30, 2017, Adams, along with [[Bruce Springsteen]], met on stage at the [[2017 Invictus Games]]. The Paralympic Games for Military Veterans, now in its third edition, saw the two artists perform for the closing ceremony at the [[Scotiabank Arena]] in [[Toronto]]. They performed some pieces of their repertoire, to close in duet performing "[[Cuts Like a Knife (song)|Cuts Like A Knife]]" and "[[Badlands (Bruce Springsteen song)|Badlands]]".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/see-bruce-springsteen-bryan-adams-sing-cuts-like-a-knife-in-toronto-120672/|title=See Bruce Springsteen, Bryan Adams Sing 'Cuts Like a Knife' in Toronto|last=Kreps|first=Daniel|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=October 2017|access-date=November 24, 2020}}</ref>

In November 2019, Adams gifted Park Walk [[Primary School]] in [[Chelsea, London|Chelsea]], England, with a new playground through his charity ''The Bryan Adams Foundation''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mylondon.news/news/west-london-news/rockstar-bryan-adams-opened-new-17357510|title=Why rockstar Bryan Adams opened a new playground in West London|date=December 5, 2019|first=Kingsley|last=Thomas|website=mylondon.news|language=en-US|access-date=November 25, 2020}}</ref> In previous years, Adams had built a [[playground]] for ''Ashburnham Community School'' in the [[Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea]] in London with his foundation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mylondon.news/news/west-london-news/bryan-adams-helps-chelsea-school-10471486|title=Bryan Adams helps Chelsea school build all-weather outdoor area|date=November 20, 2015|first=Cooper|last=Goolistan|website=mylondon.news|language=en-US|access-date=November 25, 2020}}</ref>

For his [[Shine a Light (Bryan Adams album)|Shine a Light]] world tour in 2019, Adams teamed up with shipping company DHL for an environmental project to plant a tree for every ticket sold during the course of the tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.samaritanmag.com/news/qa-dhl-exec-shines-light-eco-partnership-bryan-adams-plant-almost-million-trees|title=Q&A: DHL Exec Shines A Light on Eco-Partnership With Bryan Adams To Plant Almost A Million Trees|date=May 6, 2019|first=Karen|last=Bliss|website=samaritanmag.com|language=en-US|access-date=May 16, 2019}}</ref> In April 2020, he participates in the recording of the song "[[Lean on Me (song)|Lean on Me]]" together with an ad hoc supergroup of Canadian musicians accredited as ArtistsCAN, both in homage to the recent death of [[Bill Withers]] and for raise money for the [[Canadian Red Cross]] during the [[COVID-19 pandemic]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.iheartradio.ca/news/canadian-artists-join-voices-for-lean-on-me-1.12227470|title=Canadian Artists Join Voices For 'Lean On Me'|author=John R. Kennedy|date=April 27, 2020|website=iheartradio.ca|access-date=October 21, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/canada-lean-on-me-bill-withers-tribute-990242/|title=Justin Bieber, Geddy Lee and More Sing 'Lean on Me' in Bill Withers Tribute. Avril Lavigne, Bryan Adams and more pay tribute to late artist in charity livestream|author=Claire Shaffer|date=April 27, 2020|website=rollingstone.com|access-date=October 21, 2021}}</ref>

In November 2020, he participates with other artists in the song "[[Stop Crying Your Heart Out]]", proposed in a cover performed for the charitable cause of [[Children in Need]] under the supervision of [[BBC Radio 2]].<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.udiscovermusic.com/news/bbc-radio-2-allstars-children-in-need-single|title = BBC Radio 2 Allstars To Release Official BBC Children In Need Single|first=Paul|last=Sexton|publisher=udiscovermusic.com|date=November 10, 2020|access-date=November 20, 2020}}</ref>

=== Animal rights activism ===
During his tours of 1992–1994, Adams successfully campaigned for the [[Southern Ocean Whale Sanctuary]] with [[Greenpeace]] Chairman [[David McTaggart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.brian-fitzgerald.net/japan-cancels-whaling-expedition-go-celebrate|title=Japan cancels whaling expedition: go celebrate!|work=No Passengers}}</ref> The two of them distributed over 500,000 postcards at concerts around the world encouraging people to write to politicians of countries blocking the vote, encouraging them to vote "yes" for the creation of the sanctuary at the meetings of the [[International Whaling Commission]]. IWC officially created the sanctuary on May 26, 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weblog.greenpeace.org/oceandefenders/archive/2006/12/i_was_there_how_the_south_1.html|title=I was there: how the Southern Ocean Sanctuary came to be – Ocean Defenders – the weblog|publisher=Weblog.greenpeace.org|date=December 14, 2006|access-date=November 1, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205044426/http://weblog.greenpeace.org/oceandefenders/archive/2006/12/i_was_there_how_the_south_1.html|archive-date=February 5, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>

On November 10, 2002, Adams participated in the benefit concert at the [[Royal Opera House]] in [[London]] for the [[Digit Fund|Dian Fossey Gorilla Fund International]]. He played "[[Run to You (Bryan Adams song)|Run to You]]" and "[[Crazy Little Thing Called Love]]" with [[Brian May]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.queenconcerts.com/detail/live/1179/brian-may-live-10-11-2002-royal-opera-house-london-uk-dian-fossey-gorilla-fund.html|title=Brian May live at the Royal Opera House, London, UK (Dian Fossey Gorilla Fund) [10.11.2002]|date= November 10, 2002|website=queenconcerts.com|access-date=November 26, 2020}}</ref>

Adams in a 2007 interview for [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals|PETA]] said: <blockquote> "I've been vegetarian for about 17–18 years now, since I was about 28. And of course, my motto has always been If you love animals, don't eat them. I'm opposed to fur and any kind of use of animal products. I don't eat them, and I don't wear them. I'm not for the killing of any creature-whether it be seals, cows, dogs, anything. So anytime it comes to any kind of animal cruelty, I'm totally against it. Being sympathetic to animal rights is just something that came very naturally to me. But the moment I began to understand what was going on with the treatment of animals, it led me more and more in the way of the path I am [on] now, which is a complete vegan."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.peta.org/features/bryan-adams-animal-rights-vegan/|title=Bryan Adams on Animal Rights and Being Vegan|date=21 April 2009|publisher=[[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals|PETA]]|access-date=11 December 2020}}</ref></blockquote>

In April 2019, while off the coast of St. Vincent and the Grenadines, Adams physically intervened to protect a whale from being killed when local whalers tried to harpoon it within a conservation zone.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.everythingzoomer.com/arts-entertainment/2019/04/29/bryan-adams-whale/|title=Bryan Adams Acts as Human Shield Between a Whale and Its Hunters|website=Everythingzoomer.com}}</ref> He is the president of the ''St. Vincent and the Grenadines Environment Fund'', a non-profit company registered in [[Saint Vincent and the Grenadines]] to support sustainable initiatives to promote the preservation of the beauty and natural value of the islands.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://admin.brain-sharper.com/social/bryan-adams-saves-whale-tb/|title=Bryan Adams Saves A Humpback Whale From Poachers By Acting As A Human Shield|first=Philippa|last=Smythe|website=admin.brain-sharper.com|date=September 30, 2019|access-date=November 28, 2020}}</ref>

In May 2020, Adams was criticized for a profane social media post blaming the [[COVID-19]] pandemic on "[[Bat as food|bat eating]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/28/how-did-the-coronavirus-start-where-did-it-come-from-how-did-it-spread-humans-was-it-really-bats-pangolins-wuhan-animal-market|title=How did coronavirus start and where did it come from? Was it really Wuhan's animal market?|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=April 28, 2020|access-date=November 23, 2020}}</ref> Even though Adams did not single out any particular race in his remarks, online response was immediate and "Bryan Adams racist" began trending on social media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/pop-culture/pop-culture-news/singer-bryan-adams-slammed-racist-post-blaming-bat-eating-people-n1205166|title=Singer Bryan Adams slammed as racist for post blaming 'bat eating' people for coronavirus|work=[[NBC News]]|date=May 12, 2020|access-date=May 12, 2020|author=Aviles, Gwen}}</ref> Adams later apologized for the comments stating, "To any and all that took offence...No excuse, I just wanted to have a rant about the horrible animal cruelty in these wet-markets being the possible source of the virus, and promote veganism. I have love for all people and my thoughts are with everyone dealing with this pandemic around the world."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/bryan-adams-instagram-apology-1.5565996|title=Bryan Adams apologizes for COVID-19 Instagram post condemned as racist, inflammatory|publisher=cbc.ca|date=May 12, 2020}}</ref>

== Photography ==
[[File:LeadAward2006c.jpg|thumb|Adams accepting a Lead Award for photography in 2006]]
Adams also works as a photographer. On September 16, 2015, he was given an Honorary Fellowship of the [[Royal Photographic Society]] in London for his work in photography. Adams has been published in British ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'', L'uomo ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'', American ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', ''[[Harper's Bazaar]]'', British ''[[GQ]]'', ''Esquire'', ''[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]'' magazine and ''[[i-D]]'',<ref name="Telegraph.co.uk">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2008/03/30/sv_bryanadams.xml|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080402221237/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=%2Farts%2F2008%2F03%2F30%2Fsv_bryanadams.xml|url-status=dead|archive-date=April 2, 2008|title=The charmed life of Bryan Adams|work=The Daily Telegraph|first=David|last=Jenkins|date=March 30, 2008|access-date=April 27, 2010|location=London}}</ref> and shot advertising and PR campaigns for Hugo Boss, Guess Jeans, Sand, Converse, Montblanc, John Richmond, Fred Perry, Escada, Gaastra, Zeiss, Joop, Zeiss AG, Schwarzkopf, Ermenegildo Zegna, AGL shoes, Windsor, Jaguar and OPEL cars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://izzygallery.com/bryan-adams|title=Bryan Adams|publisher=Izzy Gallery|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://museemagazine.com/features/2018/2/21/seduced-by-the-lens-bryan-adams|title=Seduced by the Lens: Bryan Adams|website=Musée Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref>

He won three Lead Awards in Germany for his fashion photography, most recently in October 2015 for his story in Helmut Berger, and previously in June 2012 and again in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gettyimages.ca/detail/news-photo/singer-bryan-adams-smiles-during-the-lead-awards-2006-at-news-photo/57103613|title=Singer Bryan Adams smiles during the LEAD Awards 2006 at the...|website=Getty Images|language=en-gb|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> He founded the art fashion ''[[Zoo Magazine]]'', based in Berlin, for which he shoots regularly.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwd.com/eye/people/bryan-adams-head-zookeeper-8018546/|title=Bryan Adams Talks Zoo Magazine|last=Drier|first=Melissa|date=November 3, 2014|website=WWD|language=en|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref>

His first retrospective book of photos was released by [[Steidl]] in October 2012 titled ''Exposed''. Previous published collaborations include ''American Women'' (2005), for Calvin Klein in the United States; proceeds from this book went to [[Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center]] in New York City for their breast cancer research programs,<ref name="Telegraph.co.uk" /> and ''Made in Canada'' (1999) for ''Flare Magazine'' in Canada; proceeds went to the [[Canadian Breast Cancer Foundation]]. Both books were dedicated to his friend Donna, who died of the disease.<ref name="Telegraph.co.uk" />

In 2002, Adams was invited, along with other photographers from the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]], to photograph [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] during her [[Golden Jubilee of Elizabeth II|Golden Jubilee]]; one of the photographs from this session was used as a Canadian postage stamp in 2004 and again in 2005 (see [[Queen Elizabeth II domestic rate stamp (Canada)]]), another portrait of both Queen Elizabeth II and [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Prince Philip]] is now in the National Portrait Gallery in London.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.canadapost.ca/business/corporate/about/newsroom/pr/archive-e.asp?prid=971|title=Bryan Adams attends the official unveiling of the new Queen stamp|date=March 20, 2007|access-date=March 20, 2007|work=Canada Post|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070313101338/http://www.canadapost.ca/business/corporate/about/newsroom/pr/archive-e.asp?prid=971|archive-date = March 13, 2007}}</ref>

Adams supports the ''Hear the World'' initiative as a photographer in its aim to raise global awareness for the topic of hearing and hearing loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hear-the-world.com/en/the-initiative/the-ambassadors/ambassadors-up-close/bryan-adams.html|title=Interview with Bryan Adams|date=July 17, 2009|access-date=February 6, 2011|publisher=Hear the World|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110101105733/http://www.hear-the-world.com/en/the-initiative/the-ambassadors/ambassadors-up-close/bryan-adams.html|archive-date=January 1, 2011}}</ref> Adams released a photography book entitled ''Wounded – The Legacy of War'' (2013) to highlight the human consequences of war.<ref>{{cite news|author=Blackall, Luke|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/bryan-adams-book-wounded-the-legacy-of-war-shows-the-silent-legacy-of-conflict-8940461.html|title=Bryan Adams' book 'Wounded: The Legacy of War' shows the silent legacy of conflict|work=The Independent|location=London|date=November 14, 2013|access-date=December 15, 2013}}</ref>

In the summer of 2021, he shot the 48th edition of [[Pirelli Calendar]] in two working days in June in [[Los Angeles]], where most of the cast met, followed by a day of work at [[Capri]] at the end of July. The Pirelli 2022 Calendar shot by Adams is called «On the road», portrays talents from the world of music that Adams has brought together in a journey through very different nationalities, musical genres, ages and professional paths. He photographed [[Iggy Pop]], [[Rita Ora]], [[Cher]], [[Grimes (musician)|Grimes]], [[Normani]], [[Kali Uchis]], [[Jennifer Hudson ]], [[Saweetie]], [[St. Vincent (musician)|St. Vincent]] and Bohan Phoenix.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://cardealermagazine.co.uk/publish/pirelli-calendar-makes-comeback-for-2022-as-it-goes-on-the-road-with-iggy-pop-rita-ora-cher-and-grimes/230313|title=Pirelli Calendar makes comeback for 2022 as it goes On The Road with Iggy Pop, Rita Ora, Cher and Grimes|publisher=Car Dealer. August 8, 2021|access-date=August 27, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pirelli.com/global/en-ww/life/creative-powerhouse-bryan-adams-takes-on-the-48th-pirelli-calendar?_ga=2.197013100.194206001.1624731714-1750654905.1624731709|title=Pirelli: Creative Powerhouse Bryan Adams takes on the 48th Pirelli Calendar}}</ref>

Adams has also photographed many of his colleagues in the music business. Other album covers featuring work by Adams include those for:
*[[Annie Lennox]] – ''[[The Annie Lennox Collection]]''<ref>{{cite web|last=Levine|first=Nick|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/a120208/annie-lennox-to-release-first-hits-album.html|title=Annie Lennox to release first hits album|website=[[Digital Spy]]|date=August 7, 2008|access-date=December 4, 2020}}</ref>
*[[Amy Winehouse]] – ''[[Lioness: Hidden Treasures]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2011/11/bryan-adams-shot-amy-winehouses-album-cover/|title=Bryan Adams Shot Amy Winehouse's Album Cover|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|date=November 1, 2011|access-date=December 4, 2020}}</ref>
*[[Status Quo (band)|Status Quo]] – ''[[Aquostic (Stripped Bare)]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teamrock.com/news/2014-08-31/world-exclusive-status-quo-stripped-bare|title=World Exclusive: Status Quo Stripped Bare|last1=Ling|first1=Dave|date=August 31, 2014|website=Team Rock|access-date=December 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/music/status-quo-strip-down-for-album-30551334.html|title=Status Quo strip down for album|date=September 1, 2014|website=Independent.ie|access-date=December 4, 2020}}</ref>
*[[Diana Krall]] – ''[[Wallflower (Diana Krall album)|Wallflower]]''
